<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimmer Embarks on Endurance Test  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SUHR
<TEXT>
<P>
   With favorable weather and a festive send-off, triathlete and
marathon swimmer Jim Dreyer dived into Lake Erie and his latest
challenge Sunday: a plan to swim his way across two Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Michigan man, already having conquered lakes
Michigan and Huron, took to Lake Erie's chilly waters shortly
before 7 a.m. near Erie, Pa., then began stroking toward his
destination 26 miles away by waves and water.
</P>
<P>
   Should he finish that feat, Dreyer planned to run 26.2 miles and
bicycle 112 miles before swimming 31.6 more miles, this time across
Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   More than six hours and nine miles into his swim Sunday, Dreyer
was ''looking very good'' and being helped along by a friendly
current, said Bob Johnson, part of a support team that included a
42-foot vessel accompanying the athlete.
</P>
<P>
   About 8 p.m. Sunday, Johnson said shifting winds and current
caused a slight drift, slowing things a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, Dreyer had fought off cramps that began in his
calves and began working their way up his leg. They were relieved
with magnesium, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lake couldn't be any flatter than it is now, the skies are
clear,'' Johnson said Sunday afternoon. ''Lake Erie is going to be
a piece of cake for him.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:55 p.m. Sunday, Dreyer continued to make slow progress
through the cross-current and was about four miles from shore, his
Web site said. It said he was expected to reach land early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer had hoped to begin the estimated 15-hour swim Friday but
had it pushed back two days, given strong winds then. On Sunday,
Johnson called the water and weather ''very favorable,'' with waves
a bit choppy at first but calmer the farther Dreyer ventured from
shore.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting what we wanted,'' Johnson said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   His 195.8-mile journey, which he expects to take between 50 to
60 hours, will take him from near Erie to downtown Toronto. Each
segment of what he calls the ''ultimate triathlon'' will be
completed without stopping any longer than necessary to prepare for
the next segment.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Dreyer became the first person to swim a direct
crossing of Lake Michigan. Last September, he pared more than seven
hours off the record for the fastest swim across Lake Huron.
</P>
<P>
   All of his athletic stunts have been to raise money for, and
public awareness of, Big Brothers Big Sisters of America,
representatives of which bid him farewell Sunday.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Dreyer's Web site:
http://www.swimjimswim.org/framesprogress.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 0035 </TRAILER>
