<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taipei Emerging From Ugliness  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS CALO MEDINA
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- With its drab tile floors and cheap
plastic seats, the arrival hall of Taipei's airport looks more like
a bus depot in a developing country -- not the entry point to one of
Asia's most robust economies.
</P>
<P>
   More ugliness greets visitors as they finish their 50-minute
airport cab ride and pull into Taipei. Rust-stained shop signs
crawl up the facades of low-rise concrete office buildings
discolored by smog, while apartment blocks are covered with tacky
colored tiles.
</P>
<P>
   The depressing scenes would seem more fitting for one of
Taiwan's struggling neighbors, such as the Philippines or Vietnam --
not for a bustling island with the world's third-highest foreign
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   How did Taipei get this way?
</P>
<P>
   The drabness of Taiwan's capital can be explained partly by one
of the great oddities of Taiwanese history: For most of the past 50
years, Taiwan was ruled by a political party that didn't want to be
here.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nationalist Party lost China to the communists in 1949,
they fled to Taiwan and planned to use the island as a temporary
base to rearm before fighting their way back to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody thought they were going to stay forever. When you don't
consider a place your home, you don't build anything permanent or
beautiful,'' said Lung Ying-tai, a writer and director of Taipei's
cultural bureau who has lived in Europe and the United States for
21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, one of the landmark structures in Taipei is the
massive blue-tiled roof Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall, a white
marble monument to the late president who moved the Nationalist
government to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, the Nationalists, who were voted out of the
presidency last spring, had more pressing matters than spending
money to create a beautiful Taipei whose streets would rival the
boulevards of Paris or Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The government had to worry about housing a total 2 million
soldiers and refugees who fled with them. Apartment blocks made of
cheap concrete or red brick were part of the solution, and that
helped set the standards for Taipei's dull architectural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a constant threat of a communist invasion, the
Nationalists had to spend heavily on defense at the expense of
fancy public works projects. Building up the economy was also a
priority.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nationalists are widely blamed for tolerating corruption
and cronyism that sapped Taiwan's creative energy and drained funds
for public projects.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nationalists controlled the entire creative process
because it was profitable,'' said Lee Wei-min, a Harvard-educated
urban planner who had difficulty breaking into the business
dominated by old-school Nationalist planners.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I got back I realized I couldn't even design a street. I
realized I could only practice as an architect or designer, but not
an urban planner,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee said most of the interesting architecture is being built
in small, private places because Taipei wasn't planned to be a
sprawling metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taipei was meant to be a small, functional city in a remote
province of China,'' said Lee, sitting in his spare studio he
designed using steel, glass and stone.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Taipei's architectural wonders are hidden in its
labyrinthine of back streets. It's easy to stumble upon cafes and
restaurants designed with granite floors, or wood and glass panels
lit by soft halogen lamps, surrounded by manicured shrubs and
potted plants.
</P>
<P>
   Interior designer Fay Lin believes Taipei is only beginning to
emerge with confidence to create a unique image and individuality
that would eschew the previous designs of slapdash neon lights, and
shoebox apartments with aluminum cages covering their windows.
</P>
<P>
   Lin says many of Taiwan's younger entrepreneurs who had cashed
in on the dot.com frenzy have asked her to design their offices
with custom-made furniture and lighting ''that nobody else in the
world had.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Until five years ago, everything had to be functional. Period.
Now people realize money means a quality of life,'' Lin said.
</P>
<P>
   The government is also waking up to this. In recent years, it
has built grassy public parks, renovated the trendy Hsimenting
shopping district and finished constructing a subway system with
sleek stations decorated with modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Even the airport is getting spiffed up. On July 28, a second
terminal opens, featuring a bright, airy arrival hall with padded
chairs, plants and carpeted resting areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 0127 </TRAILER>
