<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio on the Senate Campaign Trail  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEATFIELD, N.Y. (AP) -- It's a gorgeous July morning in western
New York, perfect for cutting hay or milking cows. Instead, two
dozen farmers are outside a barn listening to U.S. Senate candidate
Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   As he's done at many stops, Lazio introduces his wife, Patricia,
and their two daughters, then scans the crowd for them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're having the ball of their lives,'' Lazio says of Molly,
8, and Kelsey, 6. ''They got to milk a little calf, and of course
their week is made now with that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Milk a calf? Not on any farm around here, murmur the farmers
gathered on a field in this aptly named farm town near Niagara
Falls.
</P>
<P>
   During much of his campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton, the
42-year-old Lazio's family has traveled with him. It's a strategy
that keeps Lazio from missing the comforts of home while boosting
him politically.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really do feel like I'm home when I'm here,'' Lazio tells
the farmers, unaware of the calf-gaffe. ''And I want you to know
how grateful I am for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of the four-term congressman and his family offers a
stark contrast to the Clintons, whose marriage woes are
well-chronicled. The Clinton campaign took a stab at countering the
image in late June when Chelsea Clinton showed up at her mother's
side at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillary Clinton made it clear that her college-age daughter
would not be a fixture on the campaign trail. ''She's going to be
coming and going as she chooses,'' Clinton said. ''You'll be seeing
her sometimes, which will be a delight for me, and that's all I can
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea hasn't been seen since on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for the Lazios.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lazio, who met her husband while studying to be a
nurse, even appears in the campaign's latest television commercial,
boosting her husband's stands on health care issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been busy,'' she conceded during a Buffalo Bisons
double-header. It was near the end of a weeklong bus tour that
included three Fourth of July parades and visits to factories,
hospitals and village squares.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a little bit reluctant about bringing the girls, but
they've been having such a great time,'' she said. ''And it's so
nice that we've gotten to spend some time together.''
</P>
<P>
   While many newspapers were running stories about Clinton's own
recent bus tour, the reports were played alongside pictures of a
doting Rick Lazio painting his daughter's fingernails or helping
them feed a newborn calf.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a hometown guy, he's a real person,'' said Mary Donahue,
a court clerk who attended a recent Lazio rally in Schenectady.
''Like he said, he pumps gas, he goes to the grocery store like
everybody else. ... He's winning me over.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey and Molly have become favorites of photographers who
can't get enough of the sisters -- hanging out of the ''Mainstream
Express'' bus distributing Lazio hats, T-shirts and bumper
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vote for my dad, he's great,'' the little Lazios bellowed.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio girls have grown up in a political atmosphere, joining
their dad during congressional campaigns on Long Island. But the
Senate race has taken them farther afield in one of the most
closely watched elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a once-in-a-lifetime experience for them,'' their mother
said as the pair ran to watch the antics of the Bisons' mascot.
''Just the things they've seen that they could never otherwise see
doing something like this. And the exposure and the experience has
been really fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.lazio.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.hillary2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 0129 </TRAILER>
