<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Where Bush Goes, Evans Goes, Too  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- These days George W. Bush is governor of Texas
and the presidential hope of the Republican Party, a man surrounded
by security guards and a staff that executes his every order.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans can remember when Bush was just a bad house painter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We turned on a little country and Western music and slopped
around the paint and got it a few places we shouldn't and my wife
would come in and scold us,'' Evans says with a chuckle, recalling
a scene from the 1970s at his home in Midland, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Bush has been blessed with a lot of good
friends, but Evans may be the closest.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush left Harvard Business School in the 1970s and headed
for Midland to begin an oil career, he found Evans married to one
of his elementary school classmates and ready to pal around.
</P>
<P>
   In a story that has already become campaign legend, Bush used to
hang out with Evans while Evans' wife, Susan, washed bachelor
George's clothes and made him dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1975, when Bush last flew an airplane, a bouncy
trip that proved his one-time fighter pilot skills had faded, Evans
was with him, buckled into the copilot's seat.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush quit drinking in 1986, it was after a night of
celebrating his 40th birthday with wife Laura and some close
friends -- including Evans.
</P>
<P>
   And when Bush won the Iowa caucuses, lost the New Hampshire
primary and then rebounded with a victory in South Carolina this
year en route to the Republican presidential nomination, Evans was
one of the few non-family members in the room to mark each moment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Bush is poised to announce his running mate and present
himself as his party's standard-bearer at next week's Republican
National Convention, Evans remains at his side. He was at Bush's
ranch this weekend, as the candidate did his final ''long and
hard'' thinking about choosing a potential vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Evans began as Bush's chief fund-raiser, spearheading the drive
that raised the governor more than $90 million for his campaign --
double the previous record.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he was named campaign chairman, coordinating
interaction between the staff, the national party and convention
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ''Donnie'' or ''Evie,'' as friends call Evans, has a more
prominent role than any title can signify.
</P>
<P>
   He is the straight man to his hyperactive friend.
</P>
<P>
   He is a trusted adviser who knows Bush's every mood.
</P>
<P>
   He is a soothing presence at the end of a day on the road, the
kind of guy Bush can sit back with, talking baseball or puffing on
a cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not easily excitable. He's smart. He's a successful
businessman,'' said Clay Johnson, Bush's gubernatorial chief of
staff and a friend since the governor's prep school days. ''Anybody
would welcome advice from a person like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like when Laura is around,'' the governor said during an
interview. ''I view him as somebody who knows me well, is not
afraid to give me his opinion, has my best interest at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe O'Neill, a Texas businessman who with his wife, Jan,
introduced Bush to Laura, said: ''George's plans and ambitions and
dreams meshed perfectly with Don's abilities. ... He's very
organized and yet still very fun to be with. He's not some nerd.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans was born in July 1946, as was Bush. A native of Houston,
he received a mechanical engineering degree from the University of
Texas in 1969 and a master's in business administration from the
school in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Today he heads Tom Brown Inc., an independent natural gas and
crude oil company based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush made his first foray into politics, an unsuccessful
run for Congress in 1978, Evans stepped up and raised the money. He
took on the same role when Bush ran for governor in 1994 and again
when Bush won re-election in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, less than a month in office, Bush appointed
Evans to a highly sought position in the state: the board of
regents at the University of Texas. In 1997, Evans' colleagues
voted him chairman, a position he still holds.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Evans has frequently followed Bush on the campaign
trail, talking up his friend to whomever will listen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell people he's somebody you can trust, he's an
extraordinary leader, he's got a lot of courage, but at the end of
the day, he's a real person. He doesn't take himself too
seriously,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bush be elected president, Evans is not sure what he will
do. His wife and 11-year-old son, Donnie, live in Midland. His
eldest daughter resides with her family in College Station, Texas,
while a daughter with developmental problems, 23-year-old Jenny,
lives at an adult community in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been blessed with a tremendous family. I've been blessed
with great friends. I want to share that with others any way I can,
and I see my future as a future of trying to help other people. And
if it's a role in public service, so be it. And if it's not, that's
OK, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush knows that no matter where Evans is, their bond will remain
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll be a friend whether he's in Washington or not,'' the
would-be president said. ''And he'll be a confidante, no matter
what his ZIP code is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
