<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genesee Union boosts management buyout plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A labor agreement that may ease the way
for a management buyout of the struggling Genesee Brewing Co. has
been approved by union workers at the brewery.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Teamsters Local 791 voted to support ''working with
the new management group,'' said union president Michael
Jarosinski, who declined to give specifics about the vote or the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is expected to make it easier for a team of
investors, led by Genesee Corp. chief executive Tom Hubbard, to buy
the company and keep the brewery operating in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters Local 791 represents 250 of the 450 workers at the
plant. The workers were voting on an agreement that called for some
cuts in wages and benefits, but that also kept the current pension
plan intact and would create a profit sharing plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard has presented his buyout proposal to Genesee board
members - and having an agreement with the union makes the offer
more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Genesee produces 1.6 million barrels of beer and ale a year and
had revenues of $103.3 million in the 1998-99 fiscal year. Its
brands include a line of regional beers - Genesee Beer, Genny Light
and Genny Cream Ale - as well as high-end specialty beers such as
J.W. Dundee Honey Brown Lager and Michael Shea's Irish Amber.
</P>
</TEXT>
