<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 07:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Happy With Horrors of Oz  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Terry Kinney had good reason for going into
''Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured it was always going to be surprising,'' the actor
explains three years later. ''And it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Like he has to tell that to any fan of this bare-knuckles,
bares-it-all prison drama, where surprise is mandatory. (''Oz''
airs Wednesday at 11 p.m. Eastern on HBO.)
</P>
<P>
   For the inmates of Oswald State Correctional Facility (Oz, for
short), surprise is a key to survival. And for Kinney's character,
Tim McManus, who runs the prison's experimental unit (dubbed,
correspondingly, Emerald City), surprise is an ever-present threat.
</P>
<P>
   But much to Kinney's satisfaction, McManus packs his own
surprises in the form of his shifting personality: He's caring.
Cold. Fearless. On the edge. Cheerful. Slinking in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Who IS this character?
</P>
<P>
   ''The one thing that didn't interest me was playing some sort of
idealistic do-gooder who was not conflicted, who didn't have a dark
side,'' Kinney says.
</P>
<P>
   ''What interested me was how he assimilated the prison. His
whole life has a prison metaphor. The first season he even stopped
going home. He was sleeping in his office. Smoking dope in the
halls!''
</P>
<P>
   McManus' brainchild, Em City, reflects his hopeful, progressive
approach to detention. Unlike the rest of Oz, it's modern and
bright and communal.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a basic belief that these guys are salvageable. He
believes in people being changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinney is in his dressing room in the converted factory where
''Oz'' is shot. Furnished with a cot, a mirror and two folding
chairs, Kinney's quarters are scarcely more plush than the prison
cells on the set nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Now, between sips of hot soup in one paper cup and a root beer
in another, he leans back in his chair and weighs a reporter's
question:
</P>
<P>
   Isn't McManus ultimately a pathetic figure? Granted, he fights
the good fight. But the system always has the upper hand, typically
with cruel results.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that McManus is willing to struggle isn't something
we tend to applaud in the real world,'' says Kinney, shaking his
buzz-cut head. ''People don't honor a struggle unless it pays off --
and pays off right away.
</P>
<P>
   ''But if McManus succeeds only one time out of 50, why is he
pathetic? That's not pathetic, it's heroic.''
</P>
<P>
   Of late, McManus has succeeded only in losing his job. Since the
new season began two weeks ago, he's been acting pretty nutty. Last
week, he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   McManus' woes dovetailed tactically with Kinney's need for time
off. During the spring, he directed ''One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest'' with his celebrated Chicago theater troupe, Steppenwolf, now
in its 26th season. One day a week, he flew back to shoot scenes
for ''Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in every episode this year, but I'm not around as much as
in the past,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oz'' has an enormous ensemble to take up the slack, including
Ernie Hudson, Rita Moreno, Harold Perrineau, J.K. Simmons and Lee
Tergesen. Still, McManus will likely be conspicuous in his absence:
''Let's just say I get in a lot of trouble,'' Kinney confides.
</P>
<P>
   With a distinguished career primarily in film and stage work,
the 46-year-old actor has been part of only one other series: A
decade ago, he had a recurring role as Ellyn's uptight boyfriend on
''thirtysomething.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was the male bimbo,'' says Kinney, who as soft-spoken Steve
Woodman had little to do and not a lot of screen time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The drama that brought him back to series TV is a different
story. ''A godsend,'' Kinney says.
</P>
<P>
   So is HBO, he adds. ''They're allowing us'' -- he halts, laughs
and corrects himself: ''They're not just ALLOWING us, they're
saying, 'Go farther, go farther!' That's all they ever say. They
don't think ANYTHING is too much!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's ironic that a drama about prison enjoys the most
freedom of any TV series. Violence, nudity, depravity -- it's all
there, with judicious frequency. Created and written by Tom Fontana
(also hailed for ''Homicide: Life on the Street''), ''Oz'' has
brought to television shocking language and even more shocking
images.
</P>
<P>
   A little too shocking?
</P>
<P>
   ''There are viewers who will take those elements at face
value,'' Kinney concedes, ''and they will either be disgusted, or
stimulated in a very bad, negative way.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I think Tom paints things not unlike the way they are at a
prison, in terms of the everyday life-and-death stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus does ''Oz'' rage as a world with too many fearsome choices,
yet no underlying freedom. A far-from-certain battleground between
good and evil (or, more often, between bad and badder), it boils
with many lessons. But no message is expressed more clearly and
repeatedly than this: Jail is a wonderful place to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   As a cautionary tale, then, ''I think the show does a really
good job of serving some greater good,'' says Kinney, about to
re-enter Oz to shoot a scene. ''Although I don't think art should
have to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think television should be telling people how to live.
If they're learning how to live off of TV,'' he says, ''they're
already in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.hbo.com/oz/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.steppenwolf.org/
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   NBC's 'FINEST': Richard Belzer is among several NBC stars
portraying law enforcement figures who is scheduled to take part in
the National Association of Police Organizations' seventh annual
''Top Cops'' Awards ceremonies in Washington next month. The salute
to real-life police heroes will be emceed by Belzer, who portrays
the sarcastic Detective John Munch on ''Law &AMP; Order: Special
Victims Unit.'' Other NBC stars expected to attend include Michael
Beach, Coby Bell, Bobby Cannavale, Anthony Ruivivar and Skipp
Sudduth of ''Third Watch''; Mariska Hargitay, Christopher Meloni,
Dann Florek and Michelle Hurd of ''Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims
Unit''; and Jesse L. Martin and Jerry Orbach of ''Law &AMP; Order.''
The event will specifically honor outstanding law enforcement
personnel who have been nominated from across the country for acts
of heroism and bravery.
</P>
