<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 34, Nasdaq Slips 22  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower Monday as investors
continued a downdraft that began last week after a series of
disappointing quarterly earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half-hour of trading, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 34.74 at 10,698.82.
</P>
<P>
   Among broader market indicators, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 22.69 at 4,071.76. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was down 4.29 at
1,475.90, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down
0.44 at 522.26.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are punishing the stocks of technology companies that
aren't living up to high earnings expectations. The trend began
last week, when such industry bellwethers as Microsoft, Apple and
Intel beat analysts expectations -- but just barely.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings disappointments were also the catalyst for a broad
selloff Friday, and analysts said the hangover extended into early
trading on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One shock came from Agilent Technologies, the test and
measurement spinoff of Hewlett-Packard, which said it expects
fiscal third-quarter earnings to fall way short of expectations.
Also, Ericsson AB, the world's largest maker of cellular-phone and
telecommunications equipment maker, said third-quarter profits will
fall below the first- and second-quarter levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
