<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 4; Nasdaq Dips 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed in early trading
Monday as investors continued a downdraft that began last week
after a series of disapppointing quarterly earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 3.54 at 10.730.03.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 1.25 at 1,481.44, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 2.39 at 4,092.06.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are punishing the stocks of technology companies that
aren't living up to high earnings expectations. The trend began
last week, when such industry bellwethers as Microsoft, Apple and
Intel beat analysts expectations -- but just barely.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings disappointments were also the catalyst for a broad
selloff Friday, and analysts said the hangover extended into early
trading on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   One shock came from Agilent Technologies, the test and
measurement spinoff of Hewlett-Packard, which said it expects
fiscal third-quarter earnings to fall way short of expectations.
Also, Ericsson AB, the world's largest maker of cellular-phone and
telecommunications equipment maker, said third-quarter profits will
fall below the first- and second-quarter levels.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the technology sector could get a boost Monday
from the announcement that Deutsche Telekom has agreed to pay $50.7
billion for VoiceStream Wireless Corp., giving Europe's biggest
telecom company its first foothold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty price tag for VoiceStream, which is unprofitable and
only one year old, is expected to cast a new light on other
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream wireless was seen by many as an attractive property
for Deutsche Telekom because it's growing rapidly, has licenses
covering many major U.S. markets and is not part of a larger
company.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 122.73 million
shares, down from Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.29 at 522.41.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.57 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.07 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.35 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
