<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 8; Nasdaq Adds 17  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose modestly Monday as investors
reversed course on a downdraft that began last week after a series
of disappointing quarterly earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 8.13 at 10.741.69.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 2.39 at 1,482.58, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 16.72 at 4,111.17.
</P>
<P>
   Investors spent most of last week punishing the stocks of
technology companies that aren't living up to high earnings
expectations. The trend began when such industry bellwethers as
Microsoft, Apple and Intel beat analysts expectations -- but just
barely.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings disappointments were also the catalyst for a broad
selloff Friday, and analysts said the hangover extended into early
trading on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But after a brief spate of selling, investors have started
buying. Analysts said the big picture remains relatively positive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overriding consideration has been that earnings growth has
slowed from the first-quarter pace. But, nevertheless, the majority
of S&AMP;P 500 companies that have reported second-qaurter earnings so
far have still beaten analysts' expectations,'' said Jack
Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The technology sector got a boost Monday from the announcement
that Deutsche Telekom has agreed to pay $50.7 billion for
VoiceStream Wireless Corp., giving Europe's biggest telecom company
its first foothold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty price tag for VoiceStream, which is unprofitable and
only one year old, is expected to cast a new light on other
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   VoiceStream wireless was seen by many as an attractive property
for Deutsche Telekom because it's growing rapidly, has licenses
covering many major U.S. markets and is not part of a larger
company.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 266.24 million
shares, down from Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.25 at 522.45.
</P>
<P>
