<HEADLINE> German Libraries Stock Harry Potter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAARBRUCKEN, Germany (AP) -- Harry Potter fans just can't wait
for the German translation, and now a few won't have to: A state
Education Ministry said Monday its libraries are stocking the
English edition of the latest novel about the young wizard.
</P>
<P>
   The books are in such demand that the 16 libraries in the
western state of Saarland won't loan out ''Harry Potter and the
Goblet of Fire.'' Instead, those wanting to find out what happens
in the fourth in the series of books by J.K. Rowling must read the
book during library hours.
</P>
<P>
   The state's education minister, Jurgen Schreier, said he hoped
enthusiasm for the novel would have a beneficial side-effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''Isn't this an exciting opportunity to expand knowledge of
English and at the same time satisfy curiosity?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The novel has set sales records in the United States. The first
three novels are also extremely popular in their German
translations here, occupying the top three spots on best seller
lists this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
