<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 26; Nasdaq Adds 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher Monday as investors
tried to make sense of weaker-than-expected corporate earnings
reports that conflict with indications that the threat of inflation
is waning.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 26.16 at 10.759.72.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 3.03 at 1,483.22, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 3.02 at 4,097.47.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was well below normal levels, a sign that traders
have no strong feelings one way or the other toward buying or
selling.
</P>
<P>
   Investors spent most of last week punishing the stocks of
technology companies that aren't living up to high earnings
expectations. The trend began when such industry bellwethers as
Microsoft, Apple and Intel beat analysts expectations -- but just
barely.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings disappointments were also the catalyst for a broad
selloff Friday, and analysts said the hangover extended into early
trading on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overriding consideration has been that earnings growth has
slowed from the first-quarter pace. But, nevertheless, the majority
of S&AMP;P 500 companies that have reported second-qaurter earnings so
far have still beaten analysts' expectations,'' said Jack
Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones average was up primarily on the strength of a
strong earnings report from drug company Mercks, whose shares were
up $6.063 at $69.813.
</P>
<P>
   The technology sector continued to falter Monday after Deutsche
Telekom said it will pay $50.7 billion for VoiceStream Wireless
Corp., giving Europe's biggest telecom company its first foothold
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The hefty price tag for VoiceStream, which is unprofitable and
only one year old, and fears that U.S. regulators may oppose the
sale sent both stocks tumbling. VoiceStream was down $11.375
$138.375, while Deutsche Telecom fell $5.812 to $45.688.
</P>
<P>
   Still, VoiceStream wireless was seen by many as an attractive
property for Deutsche Telekom because it's growing rapidly, has
licenses covering many major U.S. markets and is not part of a
larger company.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 239.24 million
shares, down from Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 1.41 at 521.29.
</P>
<P>
