<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Ends Border Violations  </HEADLINE>
By RODEINA KENAAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Ending weeks of border bickering, the
United Nations said Monday that Israel has pulled back from spots
where it had violated Lebanon's border, clearing the way for U.N.
peacekeepers to deploy along the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have hit a point of zero violations of the line,'' U.N.
envoy Terje Roed Larsen told reporters after a meeting with
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at U.N. headquarters in New York, Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said he hoped the peacekeepers could be deployed ''in the
next few days.'' He said he hopes to speak to Lahoud about the
deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Israel withdrew its forces from southern Lebanon two months ago,
ending an 18-year occupation intended to protect northern Israel
from cross-border guerrilla attacks. The withdrawal was supposed to
be followed by deployment of Lebanese troops and U.N. peacekeepers
to the tense border region.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lebanese government delayed the deployment, complaining
of frequent Israeli violations of its border in the form of army
patrols, military positions and moving the border fence inside
Lebanese territory. Israel also has complained of Lebanese
violations, including the throwing of stones and metal objects at
soldiers and workers along the border and attempts to cut through
the fence.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Larsen told reporters after meeting with Lahoud that
one last Israeli border violation had been rectified as he went
into the meeting. He said he expected Annan to announce UNIFIL's
deployment soon.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Lebanese and U.N. officers flew over the
U.N.-drawn border line for one last look to verify that Israel's
incursions into its territory have indeed ended.
</P>
<P>
   A statement by Lahoud's office said the Lebanese side had
requested the final verification tour before agreeing on the next
step. A meeting was scheduled for later Monday evening to discuss
the deployment of the peacekeeping force, called the United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon, or UNIFIL.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatch of peacekeepers -- about 5,000 are already deployed
north of the border in southern Lebanon -- could ease tension in the
region in the wake of the Israeli troop withdrawal. Anti-Israel
guerrillas have been the most visible armed force in the region
since the Israelis left.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that the border violations had ended was
welcomed in Israel by Aviv Shiron, spokesman for Foreign Minister
David Levy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see this as ... another step toward Lebanon assuming the
responsibility of deploying its own forces, in order to secure
order and quiet in the area and along the border,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1336 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0049 </DOCNO>
