<HEADLINE> With: BC-NJ--Internet Taxes,  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The financial auditing arm of Congress, the General
Accounting
Office, estimated in a report released Monday the amount of money
each state is losing because merchandise sold on the Internet is
not subject to sales taxes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the GAO's estimates are correct, the biggest losers are:
</P>
<P>
   -Texas, forfeiting between $26 million and $342 million this
year, and perhaps between $96 million and $1.1 billion in 2003;
</P>
<P>
   -California, estimated at $23 million to $533 million this year,
and maybe growing to $86 million to $1.7 billion in 2003;
</P>
<P>
   -New York, $22 million to $357 million this year, and possibly
growing to between $81 million and $1.15 billion;
</P>
<P>
   -Illinois, $13 million to $212 million, and perhaps growing to
$44 million to $671 million;
</P>
<P>
   -Florida, $13 million to $179 million, and maybe growing to $48
million to $595 million;
</P>
<P>
   -Pennsylvania, $12 million to $156 million, and perhaps growing
to $45 million to $505 million;
</P>
<P>
   -Ohio, $11 million to $141 million, and perhaps expanding to $43
million to $454 million;
</P>
<P>
   -New Jersey, $10 million to $155 million, and maybe growing to
$37 million to $419 million;
</P>
<P>
   -Massachusetts, $10 million to $125 million, and perhaps growing
to $25 million to $274 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
