<HEADLINE> Bus Bombing Kills Seven in India  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMRITSAR, India (AP) -- A bomb exploded in a bus in northern
India on Monday, killing at least seven passengers and wounding 20,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The bus was carrying 55 passengers when the blast occurred near
Jullundur, a city in Punjab state 200 miles north of New Delhi,
said Suresh Arora, the deputy inspector-general of police.
</P>
<P>
   The bus caught fire, but the flames were doused by a heavy rain.
The bomb was hidden in the luggage hold of the bus, said Gaurav
Yadav, the senior superintendent of police.
</P>
<P>
   There was no claim of responsibility for the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Punjab witnessed a secessionist war in 1980s by militant Sikhs.
But the Indian government controlled the insurgency in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Kashmiri militant groups fighting to secede from India also
attack buses in other Indian states.
</P>
</TEXT>
