<HEADLINE> Analysis of Lazio ad from Republican Leadership Council  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the Republican Leadership Council's
new
television advertisement boosting U.S. Senate candidate Rick Lazio:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''Health Care.''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Les Heintz.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Starting Tuesday in upstate New York television markets
(Albany, Syracuse, Rochester, Buffalo and Binghamton) and on cable
systems in the Hudson Valley and on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: Announcer: ''Democrats and Republicans agree. Rick Lazio
is a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton: ''Senator Moynihan, Representative Lazio,
thank you, sir ... Give them all a hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: Together, Lazio and Moynihan helped disabled New
Yorkers work without losing access to vital health care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lazio and Moynihan make a difference. They're from New York.
They're fighting for New York. Tell Lazio and Moynihan to keep
fighting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Lazio is shown in a conservative gray suit and tie.
There is footage of President Clinton speaking at the bill-signing
ceremony at which he praises U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio and Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan. While Lazio and Moynihan are not shown at the
ceremony, the ad features separate split-screen shots of them,
edited to appear as if they are actually side by side. The ad also
features shots of a woman in a wheelchair. At the end of the ad,
telephone numbers for Lazio and Moynihan are shown on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: This is the second pro-Lazio TV ad of New York's U.S.
Senate campaign produced by the moderate Republican Leadership
Council that counts Gov. George Pataki among its leaders. The new
ad, like the first, relies on the words of President Clinton to
praise Lazio for his work in Washington. Lazio is battling the
president's wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, for the Senate seat being
vacated by Democrat Moynihan at the end of the year. She has been
attacking Lazio's congressional record.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the first RLC ad praising Lazio, the latest one seeks to
link the congressman from Long Island with Moynihan, a popular New
York figure who has had differences with the Clinton administration
but who has endorsed the first lady's campaign. Using the
president's words to link Lazio and Moynihan allows the RLC to
tweak the first lady and possibly make the congressman more
acceptable to moderate voters who will decide the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her husband said it first. He put the names together and we
thought that makes a lot of sense,'' said Mark Miller, executive
director of the RLC. ''We're following his lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the RLC plans to spend $1 million between now and
Labor Day on such ads in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The president signed the Work Incentives Improvement Act of 1999
on Dec. 17 at the Franklin Delano Roosevelt Memorial in Washington.
In addition to Moynihan and Lazio, the president singled out six
other members of Congress for recognition at the event.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   AdWatch analysis by Political Writer Marc Humbert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
