<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senator's stand against spy draws possible threats  </HEADLINE>
dtnhrjcsy
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Federal and local authorities are
investigating possible death threats against Sen. Joseph Lieberman
by a controversial New York rabbi who has condemned Lieberman for
opposing the release of an Israeli spy, the New Haven Register
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Mordechai Friedman, head of the American Board of Rabbis,
a small orthodox rabbinical group, slammed Lieberman during a
recent public access television broadcast on Long Island. He
criticized Lieberman's public stand against the release of Jonathan
Pollard, who is serving a life sentence for passing defense secrets
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   During a broadcast of his show, ''Judaism The Series,'' Friedman
said Lieberman is evil and a traitor, and suggested there is cause
to assassinate him.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman on Monday could not comment on the ongoing
investigation, but said the threat was the most serious he had
received in public office. He said it would not affect his
activities or his position on the Pollard case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously this is occasionally the price one pays for being
involved in public life,'' Lieberman said. ''It's not going to
affect my behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Senator Christopher Dodd, attending a news conference on
another topic with Lieberman in Hartford, condemned the threat and
praised Lieberman for his position on the Pollard case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe showed a lot of courage in doing this,'' Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Capitol Police Lt. Dan Nichols said the agency has a threat
assessment division that handles such matters to determine whether
special protection is warranted, but declined to discuss the
Lieberman case.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven police said they are familiar with Friedman's
television program, but would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are aware of the television segment and we are looking into
it,'' police spokeswoman Judith Mongillo told the Register.
</P>
<P>
   Citing sources it did not identity, the newspaper said city
police have stepped up patrols in Lieberman's neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In his writings, Friedman refers to Hebrew scripture as saying
''it is permissible to execute'' someone who turns over a Jewish
person or his property to gentiles, or non-Jews, according to the
newspaper. And, whoever executes that person ''has great merit,''
Friedman asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers of the show said Friedman made similar comments
about Lieberman, who is an Orthodox Jew. Friedman also gave out
Lieberman's office phone number and said Lieberman and his family
should be cursed.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   He described his organization on his Web site as a group that
''takes on issues on behalf of Jews, Judaism &AMP; Israel that not
other rabbinical organization in America has the zealous fortitude
to tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Tad Diesel, area vice president for Cablevision Systems Corp. in
Connecticut, which owns the franchise that runs Friedman's program
on Long Island, said the company ''does not want to answer
questions on this because the matter is under police
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has called Pollard's betrayal of his country serious
breaches of law and morality. He also has said he should not
interfere in a case in which the courts have ruled. The Connecticut
Democrat was one of 60 senators including Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn. who wrote to President Clinton last year urging him not to
set Pollard free.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jewish groups have criticized Lieberman on the Pollard
case. Rabbi Michael Whitman of the Young Israel of New Haven said
the National Council of Young Israel has taken Lieberman to task
for his failure to support Pollards release.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman called it a ''respectful disagreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1445 </TRAILER>
