<DOCNO> APW20000724.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summertime and the living is - cool  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Some numbers little seen so far this summer
are showing up in the forecast for later this week: 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Buffalo's temperature hits 80 an average of 19 times
in July. As of Monday, the mercury had cracked it just twice,
according to the National Weather Service. Seventies by day and 50s
at night have been the rule.
</P>
<P>
   But before adding another page to Buffalo's poor weather
history, look around. The story is pretty much the same throughout
the Northeast and Midwest, where some are wondering what happened
to summer.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, meteorologist Steve McLaughlin said Monday, is a
shift in the jetstream that has normally retreated into Canada by
now. For the most part, any place above that ribbon of air -
including New York City, Washington and Boston - has had a cool
July. Places below - like Texas - a scorcher.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, temperatures have been running about four degrees
below normal during a July that, as of Monday, was the coolest in
50 years. (A few 80s to finish out the month may drop that a notch
or two.)
</P>
<P>
   While some are grumbling about lost beach time, there are few
complaints about perfectly comfortable weather.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who can complain about 75 and sunny?'' asked McLaughlin,
describing Sunday and Monday's weather in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is cool but we are enjoying it because we're not
hot-weather people,'' said Hildegarde Rittmann who was reading the
newspaper with her husband, Karl, at the Erie Basin Marina. ''This
suits me fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Town of Tonawanda couple had turned on the central air
conditioning in their house just once over the summer and the car
air conditioner had gotten only a few days' work.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Brown of Buffalo is hoping for at least a week of
consistent upper 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ''You want to enjoy a little hot weather,'' she said. ''I bought
all these short sets for the kids. There hasn't been much use for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest complaint has been the rain. While McLaughlin said
the July total is actually a little below normal, the rain has come
on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   There has been plenty of room to spread a blanket at the
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''On a normal hot July weekend, we would have a good 4,500 to
5,000 people between the two beaches Erie County runs,'' said Mark
Galvin, superintendent at Bennett and Wendt beaches in Evans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not getting half that,'' he said. ''It's the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Highs of about 80 were forecast for Tuesday and Wednesday, while
some rain was expected Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, meanwhile, said Buffalo residents are used to weather ups
and downs.
</P>
<P>
   ''But even for Buffalo,'' she said, ''this is a little
strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1451 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Soldier Testifies in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   GNJILANE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.S. soldier admitted in a
statement read in a Kosovo court Monday that he fired explosive
rounds into a shed where an ethnic Albanian was killed in a
shootout, offering new evidence that may clear a Serb man and his
sons on trial for the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of Mirolub ''Mirko'' Momcilovic, 60, and his sons
Jugoslav, 32, and Boban, 25, has been considered a test of whether
any non-Albanian can get a fair trial in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement read Monday, Cpl. Robert Black said he fired in
self defense into the shed where U.N. officials have said Afrim
Gagica was killed on July 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I noticed a man in the shed firing at the tower. I fired with
my M203, 40 mm high explosive rounds,'' said Black's statement.
''The second round exploded inside the shed and I kept up small,
suppressive fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Black's statement was part of a 130-page report submitted by
U.S. authorities and admitted into evidence Monday. U.S. military
and U.N. officials have offered no explanation for why it took so
long for the evidence to be submitted.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no suggestion the U.S. troops may face charges
since the rules of engagement at the time permitted NATO-led
peacekeepers to use deadly force to defend themselves and protect
Kosovo residents.
</P>
<P>
   Although the initial U.S. report said the Momcilovics were
defending their home against the victim's ''criminal intent,'' the
three men were arrested and transferred to the American detention
facility at Camp Bondsteel, where they have been held for more than
a year. In January, an ethnic Albanian magistrate ordered them to
stand trial for murder and illegal weapons possession.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Patrice de Charette of France, an international trial
judge hearing the case, adjourned the trial Monday, asking the U.S.
Army's investigation department to bring him weapons and narcotics
seized from the Momcilovic residence the night of the crime, as
well as the bullets found in Gagica's body.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the French judge, the case is being tried before
a panel of four ethnic Albanian judges. A simple majority is
required to rule on the case.
</P>
<P>
   The trial opened April 25, but the proceedings were suspended
the following day after the defense asked to introduce a security
videotape showing some of the events of the day of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. court initially refused to accept the tape into
evidence, saying it could not determine whether it had been
altered. However, after protests from human rights advocates, it
was admitted into evidence Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tape, the elder Momcilovic is shown answering the
intercom of his motorcycle repair shop and speaking with a stranger
who ultimately demanded that he come out and surrender his weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Gun drawn, a man later identified as Gagica tried to kick the
door down as a group of his armed companions looked on. An exchange
of gunfire followed. Minutes later, U.S. troops entered the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tape does not show who shot Gagica, human rights
observers had contended that it raises reasonable doubt that the
Momcilovics were responsible.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press last month, the three
jailed Serbs admitted they fired shots from a second-floor window
but said they were trying to warn U.S. troops. Terrified of attacks
by ethnic Albanians, the three Serbs insisted they were fighting
for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials have declined to comment on the case, saying they
did not want to interfere with the judicial process.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is to reconvene on Aug. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1452 </TRAILER>
