<HEADLINE> Rebels Launch Attack in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Rebels launched an unusual daytime attack
Monday, underlining their growing boldness by ambushing a Russian
military convoy in Chechnya's capital and reportedly killing
several Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian soldiers were traveling in a three-truck convoy in
Grozny when the rebels attacked, said the office of Sergei
Yastrzhembsky, the Kremlin's spokesman on Chechnya. The rebels set
off a mine under one of the trucks, then opened fire on the
soldiers with automatic weapons and grenade-launchers. The Russians
returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   Three Russian soldiers were killed and 17 wounded in the attack,
Igor Kistayev, deputy prosecutor in Chechnya, was quoted as saying
by the Interfax news agency. Yastrzhembsky's office would not
comment on casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel spokesman Mumadi Saidayev said 18 Russians were killed.
''The operation was carried out accurately,'' with no rebel losses,
he said by telephone from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the Chechnya conflict routinely exaggerate enemy
losses and play down their own.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels have stepped up attacks against Russian positions in
Chechnya in recent weeks, using explosive-filled trucks,
remote-controlled mines, artillery and automatic weapons -- but they
usually attack at night. Russian media report practically every day
that the federal forces are tightening security in the breakaway
republic, yet the attacks continue to take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Kistayev said another, similar rebel attack occurred in central
Grozny on Monday afternoon, leaving Russians wounded, Interfax
said. The report did not give more details.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent Russian success on Sunday, the military said
dozens of rebels were killed in Russian artillery strikes after
they clashed with federal forces in the forests of eastern
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting occurred nine miles east of Grozny, the military
command in the North Caucasus town of Mozdok said. The command's
press service said 42 rebels were killed in the woods there and 18
in forests in the nearby Argun region after Russian troops called
in artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   The claim could not be independently confirmed, but it could be
one of the Russian forces' biggest successes in weeks. While the
rebels have not launched large-scale operations, their series of
ambushes and bombings have sapped troop morale.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war with
independence fighters, and Moscow lost control of the region.
Troops returned in September after militants based in Chechnya
raided villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and
after about 300 people were killed in apartment bombings the
authorities blame on Chechen militants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
