<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddy Films Trade Action for Emotion  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Think movies for guys, and what comes to
mind? Tom Cruise dangling from a cliff in ''Mission: Impossible
2''? Bruce Willis blowing things up in a ''Die Hard'' thriller? Mel
Gibson and Danny Glover looking for someone to shoot in ''Lethal
Weapon?''
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   How about a chubby seducer who shares dating secrets with male
friends but ultimately recants his womanizing ways? Two brothers
offering supportive shoulders as they work through pivotal times in
their romances? A reunion between childhood chums that helps both
men exorcise boyhood demons?
</P>
<P>
   Male bonding in the movies does not just come packing a pistol
anymore. In a bullet-ridden summer that includes ''Mission:
Impossible 2,'' ''Shaft'' and ''Gone in 60 Seconds,'' there are
also smaller, intelligent movies about men getting in touch with
their feelings and thoughtfully interacting.
</P>
<P>
   Think of them as chick flicks for guys.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chick flicks allow for a degree of introspection and feelings,
which are things men weren't really acknowledged to have until
recently. Except maybe feelings of rage. Rage and lust,'' said
''American Pie'' producer Chris Weitz, who co-stars in ''Chuck &AMP;
Buck,'' a darkly comic tale of a man-child's obsession with a
boyhood buddy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which opened in mid-July, also stars screenwriter
Mike White and Weitz's brother Paul, who directed ''American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Men can be depicted now as less macho, more flawed, less
likely to inflict violence and mayhem,'' Chris Weitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 4 brings ''The Tao of Steve,'' a romantic comedy about an
overweight, underachieving lech who finds love and rethinks the
libertine preaching he's been offering his male pals. ''Smiling
Fish and Goat on Fire'' arrives a few weeks later, about two
brothers who commiserate and share advice on their love lives.
</P>
<P>
   They're all independent features playing in limited release. But
movies featuring circles of men bonding emotionally have become
more common, notably this year's ''High Fidelity'' starring John
Cusack, last year's ''Flawless'' with Robert De Niro and
''Swingers'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe it's because men of our generation, approaching 40,
they've been exposed to feminism,'' said Jenniphr Goodman, director
of ''Tao of Steve.'' which stars Donal Logue and Goodman's sister
Greer. ''Being able to express emotions more freely is probably a
consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive film portraits of male relations certainly are not
new. ''The Best Years of Our Lives'' from 1946, about three war
veterans adjusting to civilian life, and ''Midnight Cowboy'' from
1969, about the tender friendship between a country stud and an
urban gnome, both won best-picture Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   But today's audiences seem more willing to accept films showing
men in a vulnerable light.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chuck &AMP; Buck'' writer White, who stars as the emotionally
stunted Buck, said the old notion of the manly, self-contained
Hollywood hero is foreign to him.
</P>
<P>
   ''John Wayne on a prairie, the man alone, definitely is
something I can't relate to,'' White said. ''I want to love, I have
needs. Men around me in my life, they've got needs. In this day and
age, I think it's become necessary to depict that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goodman sisters wrote ''Tao of Steve'' with their friend
Duncan North, whose cool, aloof, Steve McQueen style of picking up
women inspired the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Logue, whose credits include the jilted priest in ''Runaway
Bride'' and a rebel in ''The Patriot,'' said the movie gave him the
chance to portray a potentially heartless heartbreaker in a
sympathetic light.
</P>
<P>
   ''Through the whole movie, he's teaching the tao of Steve and
telling his clueless friend to stop being such a desperate,
backrubbing guy to get women,'' Logue said. ''Then he ends up
telling him to forget everything he taught him and saying, 'I've
been trying to turn you into me, and I don't even like being me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Big hits such as ''Jerry Maguire'' and ''As Good As It Gets''
also depict men incapable of dealing with their emotions gradually
opening up with help from women and from male buddies, said Paul
Weitz.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems to be a kind of post-buddy movie movement,'' Paul
Weitz said. ''We've just kind of gorged ourselves on the 'Lethal
Weapon' sort of buddy movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher divorce rates since the 1950s may have helped men open
up, because more boys grew up in homes with mothers as the dominant
parent, said Felicia Rose Adler, author of ''Master Dating: How to
Meet &AMP; Attract Quality Men.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It used to be that boys would have been hanging out with the
men at Dad's poker games,'' Adler said. ''Now more are hanging out
with their mother's friends. They got used to that relationship
talk because women talk about those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Martini, who co-wrote and co-produced ''Smiling Fish and
Goat on Fire'' with his brother Derick and director Kevin Jordan,
joked that the trend toward more insightful renderings of men in
movies could have repercussions for films starring women.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know what it means, don't you?'' he quipped. ''It means
that women are going to have to start picking up guns and killing
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1528 </TRAILER>
