<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Presidential Hopefuls Named  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Former Prime Minister Shimon Peres and Moshe
Katzav, a one-time contender for the leadership of the hawkish
Likud party, were named Monday as candidates for the Israeli
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg announced the two candidates of the
two largest parties -- Peres, for Prime Minister Ehud Barak's One
Israel, and Katsav, for the Likud. The vote by the 120 members of
the Knesset will take place July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The previous president, Ezer Weizman, resigned July 10 in the
wake of a scandal in which he admitted receiving more than $350,000
from a French textile magnate. Although the case was closed, the
attorney general ruled Weizman had acted improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Were the election held by popular vote, the 77-year-old Peres, a
Nobel Peace Prize laureate with impressive achievements throughout
Israel's 52-year history, would win easily, opinion polls indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Peres is credited with taming hyperinflation in Israel and
ending the Lebanon war during his 1984-86 term as prime minister.
He also served as prime minister after the assassination of Yitzhak
Rabin in 1995, narrowly losing to Benjamin Netanyahu in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   However, the government coalition has lost its majority in the
Knesset and many members are opposed to the Oslo interim agreement
with the Palestinians, of which Peres was an architect. Three
parties quit the government on the eve of Barak's departure for the
Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Peres has been regarded as the leading contender for
the largely ceremonial post. Katsav, 54, who has held second-grade
Cabinet posts in Likud administrations, lacks an international
reputation and has said that if elected he would avoid politics and
devote himself to fostering domestic unity.
</P>
<P>
   The former transportation minister placed fourth in the 1993
Likud primaries that vaulted Netanyahu to the Likud leadership. He
failed to cultivate a following beyond the Iranian Jewish
community, of which he is a scion.
</P>
<P>
   If the Camp David talks continue until July 31, Peres will lack
the votes of Barak and the other Cabinet ministers and legislators
who are with him at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Burg has ruled out any postponement of the election.
</P>
<P>
   The duties of Israel's president are limited mostly to presiding
at functions, although the president has the power to pardon
convicted criminals and to name judges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1533 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Benefit From Public Outcry  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Public outrage over the
environmental damage caused by an oil spill off the coast of Cape
Town has been tempered by how well the disaster has been handled.
Of some 43,000 penguins affected by the spill, fewer than 1,000
have died.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from 1994 when 10,000 birds were coated in oil
from a spill and only half could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   While conservationists can't prevent environmental disasters
such as those caused by the Apollo Sea, which sank off Cape Town in
1994, and the Panamanian-registered tanker Treasure, which sank
June 23, they are at least coping better.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the Apollo Sea spill there was no one in charge.
Everyone was complaining it was so unorganized,'' said Jay Holcomb,
a member of an international team of wildlife experts assembled by
the International Fund for Animal Welfare to help local
organizations deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, local groups have gleaned management expertise from
international experts, and imparted their own knowledge about
penguins, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least two months before all birds are washed and
released into the wild and more will die, but already the operation
is being hailed as a success.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can say with certainty these (rehabilitated) birds do
survive,'' said Les Underhill of the University of Cape Town's
avian demography unit. ''We do know that they breed again within a
very short time.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 12,000 volunteers and many organizations can claim
credit for helping save the penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are working on a miracle here. I think we can all begin to
have more faith in mankind,'' said Estelle van der Merwe, of the
Southern African National Foundation for the Conservation of
Coastal Birds, the backbone of the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Crawford of the government's marine and coastal management
department has been praised for his decision to truck some 20,000
uncontaminated birds up the coast and release them. While the birds
swam home, workers cleaned up most of the oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a relatively easy decision. We had to get the birds
away from the oiled environment,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   That meant volunteers could concentrate on looking after the
other 23,000 oil-coated birds and chicks which had lost their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Improved catching, transporting and stabilizing methods also
contributed to the penguins' high survival rate.
</P>
<P>
   During the Apollo Sea spill, about 60 percent of the birds that
died did so within a day of being captured. Many suffocated or died
from breathing toxic fumes in poorly ventilated and crowded
transportation boxes.
</P>
<P>
   This time, specially designed and ventilated cardboard boxes
carried three penguins each. The birds were also given iron
injections, lots of fluid and kept warm.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was total panic with the Apollo Sea. This time it was a
lot better coordinated,'' said van der Merwe. ''The weather was
also on our side this time. In 1994 it was cold and wet and we did
not have enough infrared lights to dry the birds,'' which loose
their waterproofing when they come into contact with the oil.
</P>
<P>
   The technique of feeding the birds has also been refined to get
them to eat voluntarily, which most do after a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Previously the penguins were force-fed, but this was very labor
intensive and stressful for the birds, said Holcomb.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the operation's success, the spill has been a severe
setback for the African penguins, which are only found off the
coast of southern Africa and are classified as vulnerable to
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   The spill happened in the middle of their breeding cycle, and
many chicks and eggs were lost. Underhill estimates it will take
the population several years to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Merwe also warned that the birds were still vulnerable
to disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no telling what happens when you have so many birds
together in one place, but at this stage we are feeling very
positive,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
