<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb to buy French companies for $228 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. will acquire French
pharmaceutical company Groupe Chauvin and several related companies
for $228 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Groupe Chauvin, based in Montpelier, France, makes drugs for eye
care and related products.
</P>
<P>
   With combined annual sales of nearly $100 million, the privately
held companies have facilities in France, Germany, Britain,
Switzerland and Portugal, Bausch &AMP; Lomb said.
</P>
<P>
   The company added that the acquisitions will make it one of the
leading full-line eye-care pharmaceutical companies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb chief executive officer Bill Carpenter said the
Chauvin deal gives his company improved access to the European
market because of its expertise in dealing with regulators there.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb, which is based in Rochester, researches,
develops, makes and sells products including contact lenses,
lens-care solutions and eyedrops. Revenue reported for the last 12
months was $1.75 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
