<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Peacekeeper Killed in E. Timor  </HEADLINE>
By GRANT PECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- A soldier from New Zealand was shot in
the head Monday during a clash with armed opponents of
independence, becoming the first U.N peacekeeper to be killed in
East Timor and imperiling the fragile peace in the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ''That endangers everything we've been trying to achieve,''
Sergio Vieira de Mello, the U.N.'s top official on East Timor, told
journalists in Bangkok. ''This is the first combat casualty since
the peacekeeping troops arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldier, identified as Leonard William Manning, 24, a
private of the Royal New Zealand Infantry Regiment, was on a patrol
searching for a group of armed men who had reportedly crossed the
border from Indonesian-ruled West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers and the armed men clashed in the morning, and the
private's body was recovered in the late afternoon with one or two
bullets in the head, de Mello said.
</P>
<P>
   De Mello blamed the attack on ''unscrupulous extremists'' who
last year went on a spree of burning and terror after most East
Timorese voted in a U.N-backed referendum for independence from a
quarter-century of brutal Indonesian rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have our forces combing the area looking for the
perpetrators of this attack,'' de Mello said, adding that the
Indonesian army in West Timor had also been asked to block the
border and prevent the raiders from returning to their sanctuaries
</P>
<P>
   The infiltration took place near Suai, about 60 miles southwest
of East Timor's capital, Dili.
</P>
<P>
   In Dili, the commander of the 8,500-strong U.N. forces in East
Timor, Thai Lt. Gen. Boonsrang Niumpradit, described the killing as
a ''tragic loss.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to extend my condolences,'' he said in a
statement. ''Our thoughts go to the family of Pvt. Manning and to
the New Zealand contingent in East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing was the third serious attack on U.N. peacekeeping
troops since they arrived on the devastated half-island a year ago,
following the rampage by Indonesian troops and their militia
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, pro-Jakarta militiamen have regularly infiltrated
across the border to stage attacks. Much of East Timor remains a
terrorized wasteland and tens of thousands of people are refugees.
</P>
<P>
   De Mello said East Timor could have been rebuilt much more in
the past year but for ''this constant threat on the part of a small
number of thugs and extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   De Mello was taking part in a panel discussion in Bangkok with
East Timorese leaders Jose Ramos-Horta and Xanana Gusmao.
</P>
<P>
   They are attending a meeting of foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations, which Ramos-Horta said
earlier that East Timor may try to join when the territory emerges
from U.N. tutelage in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao, the former leader of independence fighters, said the
attacks showed that not everyone accepted the new democratic
government in Jakarta, which has tried to make amends for the harsh
rule of former dictator Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao said East Timor had made progress since last year but
''all this can be imperiled if problems like this morning still
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1631 </TRAILER>
