<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Court rejects group's bid to close nuclear plant  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The state's highest court - in two
decisions - on Monday ruled against environmental groups which
claim the Millstone nuclear reactors are polluting Long Island
Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court found the environmentalists had no
standing to bring the complaints to trial because they did not
first exhaust all of their administrative remedies through the
Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   ''Millstone has been the subject of department reviews,
approvals and permits for more than 25 years,'' Justice Joette Katz
wrote in the unanimous rulings. ''The plaintiffs, however, have
failed to intervene in any of those proceedings, many of which
addressed the very issues that they claim justify the trial court's
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plaintiffs cannot now benefit from this deliberate
decision to wait until the eleventh hour,'' Katz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Burton, an attorney for Fish Unlimited and other
environmental groups involved in the case, said the ruling
effectively silences citizen activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a dark day indeed,'' she said. ''In this decision, the
Supreme Court has left the stewardship of the environment to
bureaucrats who have expressed an extreme disinterest in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the groups did not file their complaints earlier
because the facts in their case developed only recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''We moved when we got the information,'' she said. ''I don't
think it's fair to fault us for that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she would ask the high court to reconsider its ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists had argued that Millstone Unit 2's cooling
system is damaging the winter flounder fishery in Niantic Bay and
Long Island Sound and that the DEP had issued an improper
wastewater discharge permit to the Millstone complex. The group
claimed the permit is invalid since the complex was idled for
months because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The groups sought to shut down the reactors or curb their
operation during fish spawning season.
</P>
<P>
   NU maintains its permits are valid and that its nuclear plant
cooling systems have a negligible impact on the fish population. A
Hartford Superior Court judge last year blamed overfishing for the
drop in numbers of fish.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new Millstone will continue its focus on the path to the
best of the best in operating our plants safely, reliably and in an
environmentally sound manner,'' said NU spokesman Joe Pillittere.
</P>
<P>
   Other parties to the appeals include the Green Party of
Connecticut; Don't Waste Connecticut; Standing For the Truth About
Radiation of East Hampton, N.Y.; the North Fork Environmental
Coalition of Mattituck, N.Y.; New York State Assemblyman Fred
Thiele of Long Island and the town of East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1636 </TRAILER>
