<HEADLINE> Texas-Okla. Border Compact Approved  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House on Monday gave its consent to an
agreement between Texas and Oklahoma that settles a two-century-old
effort to determine their common border along the Red River.
</P>
<P>
   The House, fulfilling its constitutional duty to approve
compacts reached between the states, voted by voice to accept the
agreement. The compact was formally endorsed by the Texas state
government in May, 1999, and by Oklahoma in June last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has yet to act on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Reps. Max Sandlin, a Democrat, and Mac Thornberry, a
Republican, said the boundary has been an issue since the Louisiana
Purchase nearly 200 years ago because the Red River that divides
the states changes course.
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry said an 1819 treaty with Spain, which then held what
is now Texas, set the boundary on the south bank of the river, but
the meandering river continued to cause problems. In the 1930s, the
lawmakers said, Oklahoma sent a National Guard tank to the border
where it was confronted by a Texas Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the border is to be the vegetation line on
the south bank of the Red River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
