<HEADLINE> Pataki signs law to improve school safety  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Teachers will be allowed to remove disruptive
students and required to teach civility under a new law signed by
Gov. George Pataki on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If our kids can't be safe in our public schools, where can
they be safe?'' asked Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue, a former teacher who
chairs Pataki's Task Force on School Violence.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Donohue were joined by state legislators including
Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, as well as teachers' union
officials and New York City Schools Chancellor Harold Levy at a
bill-signing ceremony at Stuyvestant High School in lower
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''One student in a classroom who refuses to learn can prevent
all of those who want to learn from having the opportunity,''
Pataki said before outlining the provisions of the law, titled
Project SAVE, for Safe Schools Against Violence in Education.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, schools will be required to adopt codes of
conduct and file them with the state Education Department.
Additionally, officials will have to report violent incidents to
the state commissioner of education. Educators also will be
required to work with local law-enforcement agencies to develop
emergency response plans.
</P>
<P>
   The law clarifies teachers' ability to remove violent or
disruptive students from the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Gerstl, legislative counsel for the United Federation of
Teachers, said teachers can now send a disruptive pupil to the
principal's office but the principal will often return the pupil to
the classroom almost immediately. ''We end up with a revolving-door
syndrome,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, Gerstl said, ''the student will stay out
until the principal determines what the appropriate punishment
should be, whether it's a suspension or something else.''
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for injuring a teacher or other school employee in
an assault is also being made more serious, as the legislation
Pataki signed raises such crimes to felony status. That's one
provision applauded by Mary Anne Durham, a teacher who suffered a
neck injury during a fight involving an angry parent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's about time legislation was passed with serious penalties
for those individuals who think that they can come into a school
and act violently toward those of us that work there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instruction in civility, citizenship and character at each grade
level is also being added to school curriculum in an effort to curb
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Future teachers and other school employees will have to be
fingerprinted and their backgrounds checked for criminal histories.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the components of the new law take effect on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   UFT President Randi Weingarten called the legislation ''the best
school safety law that this United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are kids in classrooms - and everybody who has taught
knows this - where you have 28 fabulous kids and you have one kid
you don't know what to do with,'' she said. ''You have to do
something about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
