<HEADLINE> Pataki backer accused of corrupting criminal system  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Korean-American businessman orchestrated a
scheme to buy freedom for violent Asian felons through large
contributions to George Pataki's campaign for governor, prosecutors
charged Monday.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments at the Brooklyn trial of Yung Soo Yoo,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric Friedberg told a jury the defendant
''corrupted the (criminal justice) system with promises of early
prison release.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedberg argued that Yoo - a volunteer fundraiser for numerous
high-profile Republican candidates - and a top Pataki campaign
deputy, Patrick Donohue, solicited about $40,000 in ''bribes'' from
the families of three inmates during the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-week trial, parents of the inmates testified that
Yoo guaranteed their sons would be released once Pataki was
elected. Prosecutors pointed to a paper trail of internal memos
they said proved Donohue and administration aides pressured parole
officials to fix the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo's attorney, Nicholas DeFeis, argued that there was nothing
sinister about the memos. He also noted that Donohue, the finance
director for ''Friends of Pataki,'' testified that he never
conspired with Yoo to make deals with the contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government has not proven that anyone intended to
corruptly influence these agencies,'' DeFeis said. Yoo, he added,
''has no motive or incentive to do this ... He's just not that
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoo, 63, of Glen Ridge, N.J., faces up to 10 years in prison if
convicted on campaign corruption and obstruction of justice
charges. The jury was expected to begin deliberating on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoo case stems from an ongoing grand jury investigation of
an alleged influence peddling by Pataki aides in parole cases. So
far three parole officials have been either charged or convicted.
</P>
<P>
   No one close to Pataki, including Donohue, has been charged. The
administration has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
