<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Double tragedy: Drunken driver returns to road, kills Navy ensign  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSGROVE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - The driver at fault in a
head-on collision that killed a U.S. Navy officer had been cited
for drunken driving hours earlier, state police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Pangle, 37, of Woodstown was charged with driving under
the influence after registering a blood-alcohol content of 0.21
percent - more than twice the limit for drivers - at about 10:30
p.m. Saturday, according to John Hagerty, a spokesman for the state
police.
</P>
<P>
   Pangle was arrested after a caller notified state police that
someone in a black 1987 Chevrolet Blazer was driving aggressively
and erratically on Gerschel Avenue in Pittsgrove, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes after the call came in at 10:07 p.m., Trooper
Robert Gates spotted the vehicle parked along the same street.
Pangle flunked a sobriety test and was taken to state police
barracks, where he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Powell, 38, of Pennsville, a friend of his, was
contacted and came to the station to pick up Pangle. He told police
he would take Pangle home, but he took him back to the vehicle on
Gerschel Avenue, Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:23 a.m., Pangle was behind the wheel when his truck
collided head-on with a car driven by Ensign John R. Elliott, 22, a
recent graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy at Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Pangle's westbound vehicle clipped a passing trailer
and then hit Elliott's vehicle head-on. Both were killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's passenger, Kimberly Hohenwarter, 22, of Westminster,
Md., survived the wreck. She was listed in critical condition
Monday in the intensive care unit of Cooper Hospital-University
Medical Center in Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was charged with allowing an intoxicated person to
operate a motor vehicle. Prosecutors haven't decided yet whether to
file criminal charges, according to Michael Ostrowski, chief of
trials for the Salem County prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ostrowski nor Hagerty could say whether Pangle drank
again after his arrest. He left the station at 12:40 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology tests will be performed on his body but the
blood-alcohol content will not be known for several weeks, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a traffic incident in which innocent individuals need
not have been killed or injured,'' Hagerty said. ''Had Mr. Powell
fulfilled his obligations and responsibilities, certainly Mr.
Elliott and his passenger would not be deceased and severely
injured today.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell was sober and possessed a valid driver's license when he
arrived to take custody of Pangle, Hagerty said. That is where the
police's responsibility ended, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, a 1996 graduate of Egg Harbor Township High School, was
a former National Merit Scholar, class president and a football
player. He was to attend flight school at Pensacola, Fla., in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has just ripped a piece of our life from us,'' said his
father, Bill Elliott, director of marketing and development at
Shore Memorial Hospital in Somers Point. ''We are not bitter or
angry. We are just so, so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our community, our nation, is all the poorer for his loss,''
said Richard Pitman, president of Shore Memorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1705 </TRAILER>
