<HEADLINE> Hollinger International sells three newspapers to new company  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - The Times Herald of Olean, the Salamanca
Press, Salamanca Penny Saver and the Bradford (Pa.) Era have been
sold by Hollinger International Inc. to the newly formed Bradford
Publications Co.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford Publications is led by John Satterwhite, publisher and
editor of the Bradford Era; Conrad Black, chairman of Hollinger
International of Toronto, and F. David Radler, publisher of the
Chicago Sun-Times, president of Hollinger and chairman of its
subsidiary American Publishing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ''Local ownership is returning to these properties and I think
that will be good for the community,'' Satterwhite said following
the sale's completion last week.
</P>
<P>
   Satterwhite said the newspapers' operations would continue
unchanged while the new owners look to improve content and
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the sale were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal will be to strengthen the franchises in each market
by concentrating on services to our readers and advertisers,''
Satterwhite said.
</P>
<P>
   American Publishing had owned the Bradford and Salamanca
newspapers since 1986. The Hollinger subsidiary acquired The Times
Herald in 1995 from Thomson Newspapers, which bought it in 1988
from the Fitzpatrick family of Olean.
</P>
<P>
   Hollinger said in April it would sell most of its community
newspapers in the United States and Canada. At the time, it owned
77 paid daily newspapers, including the Chicago Sun-Times, the
Daily Telegraph in London and the Jerusalem Post. It also held 302
non-daily newspapers, plus magazines and other publications.
</P>
</TEXT>
