<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infected mosquitoes found in Central Park, Staten Island  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Mosquitoes carrying the West Nile Virus have
been found in Central Park and on Staten Island, prompting city
officials to order the park closed Monday night and canceling a
concert that had been expected to draw 30,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The city was scheduled to spray the park with insecticide
beginning at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As a precautionary measure, on Wednesday, the ground spraying
will expand to Manhattan between 23rd and 110th streets. Spraying
previously scheduled for Staten Island on Monday night and parts of
Queens and Brooklyn on Tuesday will also take place.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said residents should not be alarmed by
the discovery of infected mosquitoes or the ground spraying of the
synthetic pesticides Sumithrin and Resmethrin, which could cause
breathing problems for the elderly and people with respiratory
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public should not have a great deal of apprehension,''
Giuliani told a City Hall press conference. ''Go about your lives
normally, but for one night, stay out of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   The park will close at 9:30 p.m., postponing a free performance
by the New York Philharmonic and a road race for children that had
been scheduled. Giuliani said the concert would likely be held
tomorrow evening.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of rain, spraying will take place Tuesday night,
said Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of infected mosquitoes marks the first time that
the deadly West Nile virus has been found in mosquitoes in the city
this year. Earlier this summer, the virus was found in birds and
mosquitoes in the suburbs that ring the city.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the West Nile virus killed seven people and infected
62 others in the New York metropolitan area, prompting the city and
neighboring areas to undertake a massive campaign of aerial and
ground spraying.
</P>
<P>
   To staunch a new outbreak this year, the city embarked on a
program of trapping and testing mosquitoes and placing flocks of
sentinel chickens around the city in order to detect the presence
of the virus early and by placing mosquito larvae eating fish in
water treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious cases, the West Nile virus causes infection
resulting in encephalitis, or swelling of the brain. Elderly
individuals or those with weakened immune systems are most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The infected mosquitoes were found in Central Park near 63rd
Street on the east side of the park; and in Staten Island in the
Fresh Kills landfill and Pond Park.
</P>
<P>
   Despite protests about the insecticides' potential risk to human
health and animal life, Giuliani said he was primarily concerned
with human life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to wait until it shows up in human beings like
it did last year,'' said Giuliani. ''And I'm sorry, but if it kills
animals, it kills animals. My job as mayor of New York City is to
help protect human life as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the mayor's announcement, Central Park was filled
with people clad in T-shirts, tank-tops and shorts. Young men and
women lounged on the grass, parents watched over their children,
and several elderly women rested in their wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Few people were concerned by the news.
</P>
<P>
   As Ellen Wheatley looked after her playful 3-year-old daughter,
Allison, she wondered what really could be done.
</P>
<P>
   ''What can I do about it - kill myself with (bug spray)?'' said
Wheatley, who was vacationing in Manhattan from her home in
Washington state. ''We already got chewed up by the bugs on the
Jersey shore, so maybe they already got us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1746 </TRAILER>
