<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Talk of Statehood  </HEADLINE>
By IBRAHIM BARZAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Should the Camp David summit fail,
the Palestinians plan to declare a state in less than two months
that would include lands still controlled by Israel, a senior PLO
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will tell the world that all of our land is under the
umbrella of the Palestinian state, including the land that Israel
should withdraw from,'' said Salim Zanoun, the chairman of the
Palestine National Council, the PLO's legislative body. ''We will
consider this land occupied land of the (Palestinian) state.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement was a new twist in Palestinian talk of a future
state. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and others have repeatedly
pledged to declare statehood by the Sept. 13 deadline for a final
peace agreement, but they have left open the possibility that such
a declaration would not define borders, which would leave the door
to negotiations open.
</P>
<P>
   A declaration encompassing Israeli-controlled land, however,
could invite a retaliatory annexation by Israel -- and that could
lead to an outbreak of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to elaborate on his statement Monday, Zanoun said the
''occupied'' lands include lands the Palestinians believe are due
them under interim peace agreements. Palestinians control about 40
percent of the West Bank, and say interim agreements would bring
them another 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Israel regards such lands as open to negotiation in a final
agreement. Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said a unilateral
statehood declaration could prompt Israel to annex some West Bank
lands.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel on Monday, Barak's hard-line opponents -- including
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu -- again urged him to avoid
far-reaching concessions at the U.S.-mediated talks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such calls, a poll published in the daily Maariv Monday
showed that 59 percent of Israelis want some kind of deal reached
at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   There were 590 respondents in the poll, conducted by Gallup,
with a margin of error of 4.5 percentage points. Thirty-one percent
would prefer to see the summit fail, and 10 percent said they don't
know, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli spokesmen have expressed a cautious optimism about
success at the summit, but one of Arafat's advisers dismissed that
as misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ''Up to this moment we did not reach any conclusion,'' said
Tayeb Abdel Rahim, a top aide who is in daily phone contact with
the Palestinian leader. ''I can say the situation there is
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Rahim said the stumbling block was Barak's refusal so far
to concede Palestinian sovereignty in east Jerusalem, claimed by
the Palestinians as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Christian and Palsestinian leaders in Jerusalem demanded Monday
that all of east Jerusalem -- including the Old City, where Muslim,
Jewish and Christian holy sites are located -- should be given to
Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Old City is part of east Jerusalem. All of east Jerusalem
... is Palestinian,'' said the statement, which the local heads of
the Roman Catholic, Greek Orthodox and Armenian Churches joined.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian spokeswoman Hanan Ashrawi, who returned from
Washington last week, said the sides should begin lowering
expectations, and prepare for yet another of the interim deals that
have characterized the peace process since its launch in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   She said negotiators should aim for ''either some kind of vague
framework or damage control to prevent a total breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   In the disputed territories, each side has accused the other of
stepping up military activity.
</P>
<P>
   Waji Afouni, a security official in the West Bank town of Nablus
who trains youths in guerrilla techniques at summer camps, says the
Palestinians have lost patience after years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Israeli government continues to (deny our rights),
maybe we will find ourselves in the future forced to defend our
rights and get it back by violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers say they have recently purchased flak jackets
and night vision equipment in anticipation of an increase in
hostilities if the summit fails.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1839 </TRAILER>
