<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels in Sierra Leone Surrender  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Dozens of rebel fighters, many of
them children, emerged without warning from the jungle and
surrendered to U.N. forces in wartorn Sierra Leone, U.N. officials
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Revolutionary United Front rebels accompanied by 22
child combatants turned up Saturday in the government-controled
eastern city of Kenema and handed over their weapons to U.N.
forces, U.N. spokeswoman Hirut Befecadu said.
</P>
<P>
   More fighters surrendered the same day at a disarmament facility
in the eastern town of Daru, though Befecadu could not say how
many.
</P>
<P>
   No further details were immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, members of the group that reignited the country's
bloody 8-year civil war in May, gave no reason for their decision
to disarm, Befecadu said.
</P>
<P>
   The move, however, came after the 13,000-strong U.N. force began
using force this month to maintain order -- and to restore its
credibility after the humiliating capture of hundreds of its
peacekeepers in May.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a U.N. operation successfully freed the last
233 U.N. troops who had been surrounded for weeks in the eastern
rebel stronghold of Kailahun. One Indian U.N. peacekeeper was
killed and seven injured in the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a ragtag alliance of pro-government fighters
continued to push the rebels away from the capital, Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Government soldiers recaptured the western town of Lenge Koro on
Thursday, army spokesman Maj. John Milton said. One soldier was
killed and 11 rebels were captured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have killed tens of thousands of civilians and
systematically maimed many more in bid to oust the government
through terror. They have abandoned three peace treaties, the
latest signed in July 1999, since launching their campaign in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
