<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Might Miss Asia Trip  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP)-- The open-ended Mideast summit at Camp David
jeopardizes a trip to Asia by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and a chance to quiz North Korea's foreign minister on whether the
country's ominous missile program can be diverted to civilian use.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is at the peace talks ''for the duration,'' State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Monday as President
Clinton and Albright pursued with Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators their detailed stands on such core issues as the future
of Jerusalem and the boundaries of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are taking this day by day,'' said White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Albright had hoped to go to Bangkok, Thailand, for a meeting of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and a talk with North
Korea Foreign Minister Paek Nam-Sun.
</P>
<P>
   She also had tentative plans to make a stop in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   If the summit ends shortly, she should be able to make the trip,
but as the talks go on, the possibility of scrubbing it increases.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's deputy, Strobe Talbott, remained in Kapan after the
conclusion of the G-8 economic summit meeting, on call to replace
Albright on the Asia trip.
</P>
<P>
   The high-level contact with North Korea reflects an improvement
in relations between the United States and a country long-denounced
as being headed by a ''rogue regime.'' The State Department stopped
using that reference after North and South Korea began
reconciliation talks during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright and others in the Clinton administration still
described North Korea as a potential foe and a prime reason for
considering an expensive system to defend the United States against
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   After a trip to Pyongyang, Russian President Vladimir V. Putin
said North Korea had offered to abandon its missile program if
other nations would provide it with rockets to launch satellites
into space.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton talked to Putin in Okinawa, and Boucher said Monday ''we
got some clarifications.'' But, the U.S. official said, ''there are
still quite a few questions'' to take up with North Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
