<HEADLINE> Franks says Corzine's ''universal'' proposals would bankrupt country </HEADLINE>
o0123nyc--
u n BC-NJ--SenateRace     07-24 0697
BC-NJ--Senate Race,Bjt,670
Franks says Corzine's ''universal'' proposals would bankrupt
country
By NANCY PARELLO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - With one of Capitol Hill's most prominent
budget experts at his side, Republican U.S. Senate candidate Bob
Franks said his opponent's ''universal'' proposals would ''bankrupt
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But he failed to offer any concrete alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, accompanied by House Budget Committee Chairman John
Kasich, R-Ohio, acknowledged voters want ways to improve education
and health care. He promised to forward his own detailed proposals
sometime soon.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Franks confined his comments to criticizing
Democratic candidate Jon Corzine's proposals to provide
''universal'' health care, long-term elder care and public
preschool, estimating the programs would cost $756 billion, or
about $4,900 per taxpayer, per year.
</P>
<P>
   ''In one year, Jon Corzine's spending would bust the federal
budget,'' said Franks, a Congressman from Union County.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich backed him up, calling Corzine's plan a ''dinosaur'' that
is so free spending it would fail to find support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could never go to Washington with this thing,'' Kasich
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Corzine camp said Franks' numbers are skewed and, in
some cases, go beyond Corzine's actual proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''What Jon has said is he supports universal long term health
care, education and preschool, within the context of a balanced
budget and in a way that allows us to pay down the debt and
preserve Social Security and Medicare,'' said Tom Shea, campaign
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Corzine is not immediately proposing providing
government-financed long-term care for all the elderly, Shea said.
At first, Corzine simply wants to give a $3,000 tax credit to
families who are caring for aging kin.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine also calls for other reforms, such as lowering the cost
of private long-term care insurance and changing federal spending
to help more seniors stay in their homes, instead of being forced
into nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   But, referring back to Corzine's campaign ads promising
''universal'' services, and pulling numbers from a variety of
sources, including Corzine's own Web site, Franks offered some
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   He said providing long-term care to every needy elderly American
would cost $550 billion a year. That's $50,000 for 11 million needy
elderly Americans - figures taken from Corzine's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Franks also estimated that Corzine's call to give all Americans
access to health care would cost $110 billion. He arrived at that
figure using different sources, including research from the Urban
Institute, to calculate the cost of providing insurance to all
uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine's platform, outlined on his Web site, isn't quite
that ambitious. Instead, he calls for covering all children and
forcing employers to provide health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Franks' pegs Corzine's plan for ''universal'' college at about
$50 billion, in addition to the $8 billion the federal government
already spends on college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   But Franks' calculation overlooks Corzine's call to restrict
scholarships to students with a ''B'' average, which would lower
the number of eligible high school seniors.
</P>
<P>
   On preschool, Franks said it would cost $38 billion per year to
provide public preschool to every 3- and 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes a 90 percent participation rate, translating to 6.8
million preschoolers, according to U.S. Census Bureau figures. It
assumes half would attend full day, while half would go half day.
The estimate is based on a cost of $8,415 per child - the average
per pupil spending, according to the National Center for Education
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine doesn't specifically call for giving preschool to
every child - at least not right away. Instead, he is initially
proposing doubling the size of Head Start, the federal preschool
program for poor children.
</P>
<P>
   Franks also suggested that Corzine was unwilling to debate him,
but Shea said they are waiting to hear back from the Franks'
campaign to set up a debate schedule.
</P>
<P>
   On the net://
</P>
<P>
   www.votecorzine.com
</P>
<P>
   www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1845 </TRAILER>
