<DOCNO> APW20000724.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lautenberg begins to forge legacy with donation of papers to Rutgers </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg donated
his collection of official papers from his 18-year Senate career to
Rutgers University on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, D-N.J., has begun to take steps to forge his legacy
in New Jersey as his third Senate term comes to an end this year.
He decided to retire last year after determining he did not have
the time or the heart to raise the funds required to wage a strong
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not happy about it,'' Lautenberg said Monday of his
retirement. Referring to the campaign spending of the Democratic
nominee for his seat, Jon Corzine, he said, ''Perhaps if I had
known then what I know now, I can think of several million reasons
why this decision may have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg summed up his career to a room of Rutgers
administrators Monday, citing the 1990 legislation that banned
smoking on airplanes and 1984 legislation that raised the drinking
age to 21 as key accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   His legislation ''may look narrow on the surface,'' he said, but
said the impact of a smoking ban on airplanes and the higher
drinking age has saved thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg also authored legislation that banned convicted
domestic abusers from owning a gun, and helped write the Superfund
Clean Air and Safe Drinking Water acts, as well as the Balanced
Budget Agreement of 1997 that helped produce the first balanced
budget since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not bad stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The papers - 2,000 cubic feet of them - will include drafts of
those bills, as well as correspondence, speeches and photographs
documenting his career, that ''form a window in the process of
American politics during two full decades,'' said Rutgers President
Francis L. Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg spoke next to a photograph of himself at the podium
announcing the signing of the Balanced Budget Act with President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore in the background. The
photograph is framed with a thank-you note from Clinton and the pen
he used to sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers officials say it will take nearly two years to go
through the material, which is still in Washington. When it is
ready, it will become part of Rutgers' Special Collections and
University archives, which also houses the papers of the
congressional careers of Millicent Fenwick and former Gov. Jim
Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, a self-made millionaire and owner of a payroll
services company, defeated Fenwick in 1982 to win an open Senate
seat after serving for four years on the board of the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey. He is the senior Democrat on
the Senate Budget Committee and also serves on the Appropriations,
Environment and Public Works and Intelligence committees.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg said he considered donating the materials to his alma
mater, Columbia University, but decided that he wanted to leave his
mark in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the people who sent me to represent them in
Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is running against Republican U.S. Rep. Bob Franks to
succeed Lautenberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 1846 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0120 </DOCNO>
