<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Says Capitol Suspect Worsens  </HEADLINE>
By DERRILL HOLLY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A psychiatrist testified Monday that Russell
E. Weston Jr., accused of killing two police officers inside the
national Capitol, spends his time sitting emotionless, often mute,
in a federal prison hospital, his mental state clearly
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, 43, sat silently as Capt. Sally Johnson, forensic
psychiatrist with the U.S. Public Health Service, said in a
District of Columbia courtroom: ''I'm warehousing Mr. Weston in a
psychotic state.''
</P>
<P>
   As an associate warden at the hospital in Butner, N.C., Johnson
has observed Weston for almost two years. He was judged incompetent
to stand trial 4&AMP;frac12; months after officers John M. Gibson and Jacob J.
Chestnut were shot to death July 24, 1998, inside the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's evaluation led to the incompetence judgment. She also
is the author of the psychiatric report asserting Unabomber
Theodore Kaczynski was competent for trial.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, Johnson painted a picture of a profoundly
disturbed man who continues to express a ''highly delusional belief
system.'' In addition to claiming an ability to control and even
reverse time, he has said he has been targeted by the Central
Intelligence Agency, and the government has placed listening
devices in his teeth and put atomic weapons around his Montana
cabin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Emmet Sullivan is holding hearings to
determine whether Weston should be medicated forcibly in an effort
to make him competent for trial.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the D.C. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that Sullivan
would have to consider possible side effects of medical treatment.
The court also ordered the judge to consider whether Weston's
improvement would aid his ability to assist with his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without anti-psychotic medication, it is unlikely that he will
ever be competent to stand trial,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Weston has refused for more than a year to take medication. He
also has refused to participate actively in physical therapy
designed to help him recover from wounds sustained during a gun
battle in the Capitol. He uses a walker and wears a brace on his
left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ''He will stay in his bed and hide under his blanket,'' Johnson
said. At Butner, Weston is secluded because he is considered a risk
to other prisoners. He also is kept under a 24-hour suicide watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
