<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Broadcaster Summerall To Retire  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fifty years of involvement with the NFL might
be enough for Pat Summerall. Then again, they might not.
</P>
<P>
   Summerall announced his retirement -- sort of -- as an NFL
broadcaster Monday, effective after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   His final assignment for Fox Sports will be the play-by-play
call of the Super Bowl in January 2002. As the 70-year-old
Summerall made clear at a news conference, however, nothing is
etched in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really is Pat's call, Pat's decision,'' said David Hill,
the chairman of Fox Sports Television Networks. ''We'll do the next
two seasons with Pat and John (Madden).
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever happens after two years, it's Pat's call. It doesn't
get any better than Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerall and Madden, a former head coach of the Oakland
Raiders, have been one the most prominent sports television teams
for 19 years, calling NFL games at CBS for 13 seasons and at Fox
the last six.
</P>
<P>
   Summerall and Madden have broadcast seven Super Bowls -- more
than any other network broadcasting team. In total, Summerall has
worked 15 Super Bowls on network television -- the first five as a
game analyst and the rest doing play-by-play.
</P>
<P>
   His contract expires after the upcoming season. Fox will give
him a one-year extension that will allow him to call a record 16th
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He will have completed 50 years of involvement with the NFL
following next season, 10 as a player and 40 in the broadcast
booth.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be 50 years in the NFL, I don't know if anyone's
ever done that before,'' he said. ''That's the story. I was sure
that next year would be the end of 50 years. This is 20 years with
John.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not retiring from broadcasting. I'll miss it, but I'm not
sure I'm going away from it. I want to take another look. I'm not
sure what I want to do at the end of two years. My health is good.
There might be other sports I might be getting involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he might call football games after next season,
Summerall replied: ''If after two years I still feel as good about
football, as enthusiastic, that's a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerall said he'd like to be involved in golf, a sport he
announced for CBS. Fox doesn't carry golf.
</P>
<P>
   Summerall, who plays a lot of golf, feels much better physically
after undergoing left knee replacement surgery nearly five months
ago -- his 10th surgery on an old football injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''Twelve pounds of titanium in there,'' he said with a smile.
''I set off every alarm in every airport.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he stays in shape by, among other things, doing
1,000 sit-ups a day in front of the television. He said it takes
him about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy for him,'' said Summerall's wife, Cheri. ''When we
started talking about it, it was the 50 years. We decided to take a
look, see where we are after two years. We decided to make it a
celebration, not a retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been sober for over eight years. His health is better
than it's ever been, better than mine. Every day he gets up happy,
he keeps me grounded. He enjoys every single day.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerall became a play-by-play announcer in 1974 strictly by
accident. He was working with Jack Buck, and CBS boss Bob Wussler
said the two sounded too much alike.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'As long as you want to make a change, I'd like to do
play-by-play,''' Summerall recalled. ''He said OK. It was a
Wednesday. I did a game the next Sunday with Tom Brookshier.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerall's transformation to sobriety has been well-documented.
After an intervention involving, among others, former NFL
Commissioner Pete Rozelle, CBS head Peter Lund, and PGA leader
Deane Beman, he checked into the Betty Ford Clinic in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no intention of quitting, I was having too good a
time,'' Summerall said. ''I'm sure I'd be dead if I hadn't stopped.
The prescribed stay at Betty Ford is 28 days. They kept me 33
because I was so angry at the people who did the intervention, the
first five days didn't do me any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerall was a place-kicker and tight end for the Chicago
Cardinals and New York Giants for 10 seasons. He has been
announcing NFL games since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's more than a play-by-play announcer, Pat is football,''
Madden said. ''If it wasn't for Pat, I wouldn't be in this business
for so long. Pat Summerall is the easiest man to get along with
I've ever met in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
