<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Criticized for Egg Irradiation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration has approved
irradiation of eggs to kill harmful bacteria even though the
process can lower nutritional content.
</P>
<P>
   In making the decision, which was effective last Friday, FDA
found that irradiating eggs would cause no harmful side effects.
Although the eggs would contain less vitamin A, the agency said,
people generally get enough of the nutrient from other foods.
</P>
<P>
   A consumer advocacy group criticized the agency's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''The all-American breakfast is quickly becoming the
all-irradiated breakfast. The FDA's decision is not only
scientifically irresponsible, but it is an insult to Americans who
expect to wake up in the morning to a fresh, wholesome meal,''
Wenonah Hauter of Public Citizen said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Irradiation, already approved this year for meat, can lower the
level of salmonella bacteria in eggs, FDA said.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs pasteurized with hot water to kill the bacteria are
available in limited markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
