<HEADLINE> Philippine Cops Break Up Protests  </HEADLINE>
By OLIVER TEVES
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Riot police used truncheons and water
cannons Monday to break up anti-government protests by several
thousand people ahead of the president's state of the nation
address.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 police officers were deployed to prevent the
protesters from disrupting President Joseph Estrada's speech in the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Police dispersed a group of about 500 supporters of the
left-wing New Patriotic Alliance on a road leading to the House,
hours before the speech. Several protesters and at least one
newspaper photographer were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Several miles away, police sprayed water cannons at protesters
from other left-wing groups who attempted to leave a park where
they had been allowed to rally.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance called the protests to demand Estrada's ouster and
blaming him for deterioration of the economy and what it called
''social instability.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada devoted much of his state of the nation address to
Mindanao, saying he would seek peace with the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front, but only if the rebels abandon their goal of an
independent Islamic state, stop criminal activities and disarm.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Estrada headed to the United States for an
eight-day visit, during which he will meet with President Clinton
and Defence Minister William Cohen. Estrada will also meet in San
Francisco with the heads of several Silicon Valley companies in a
bid to drum up greater investment in his country.
</P>
<P>
   Business confidence in the Estrada administration has plummeted
because of weaknesses in the economy and because of the crisis in
the southern region of Mindanoa, where the government is battling
Muslim separatists.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, he offered greater autonomy to the Mindanao
rebels and help with economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will write a new history for Mindanao,'' Estrada said. ''We
will rectify centuries of historical wrongs committed by successive
colonial powers, and decades of inequities committed by successive
Philippine governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada said his next battle would be against corruption, which
remains a major problem for the government.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I believe the Philippine economy needs is not just
reforms, but radical restructuring from the ground up'' to remedy
decades of misdirection, mismanagement and corruption, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
