<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ark-Monticello Losing Streak Widens  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTICELLO, Ark. (AP) -- It may be the middle of summer, but
Arkansas-Monticello's football losing streak just got 11 games
longer.
</P>
<P>
   The streak reached 33 games Monday when the school forfeited its
four victories from last season for eligibility and financial-aid
violations.
</P>
<P>
   The Boll Weevils had a 22-game losing streak entering the 1999
season -- the nation's longest losing streak at the time -- and beat
Stillman College 30-7 last Sept. 4. Stillman was playing its first
game in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   That, plus three other victories, were wiped out and instead of
a 4-7 season, the school listed its record as 0-11.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's 21-game losing streak still will be listed as
the longest current string in the nation, the NCAA said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Campbell, a statistician at the association's headquarters
in Indianapolis, said the NCAA will not count the additional losses
for Arkansas-Monticello because the forfeits were on the school's
initiative and not the result of NCAA sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   School spokesman Jim Brewer said three players took only 11
hours during the spring semester of 1999. NCAA regulations require
that student-athletes take 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Brewer said, work-study funds for two of the athletes were
paid for out of athletic department funds in violation of Gulf
South Conference and NCAA violations. The payments -- $247.20 for
each athlete -- would have been OK if they had come from any other
university account, Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said that while the school was ''technically'' 0-11 last
season, it still would note in its records that it was 4-7 on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas-Monticello Chancellor Fred Taylor said that, in
addition to the forfeits, the Boll Weevils imposed additional
sanctions. They include excluding UAM from a conference television
package, paying the league double the amount of money paid to the
athletes and limiting recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We deeply regret these violations and have taken steps to
ensure that these types of infractions do not occur again,'' Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The school said it would be eligible to compete for the Gulf
South Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Stillman game, the Boll Weevils forfeited
victories over Southern Arkansas (23-20), Valdosta State (35-31)
and West Alabama (23-17).
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said the NCAA was still reviewing the players'
eligibility status for the 2000 season. The Boll Weevils open the
season Sept. 2 at Tusculum College in Greeneville, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1915 </TRAILER>
