<HEADLINE> Donovan McNabb Leads Eagles  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- Donovan McNabb was nearly booed out of
Philadelphia just seconds into his Eagles' career. A year later,
he's won over the fans and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, the No. 2 pick in the 1999 NFL draft, has a strong arm
and tremendous athletic ability. But it's his confidence and
maturity that's made him the team leader in just his second season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's taken that responsibility on his shoulders to be the
leader,'' said Koy Detmer, the starting quarterback before McNabb
and Doug Pederson arrived in Philadelphia. ''It's not something he
works hard to do. He's a natural. He's not a rah-rah guy. He enjoys
having fun and guys follow his lead, his example.''
</P>
<P>
   In a football-crazed town starved for a winning team and a true
hero, McNabb is ready for the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   While troubled stars Eric Lindros of the Flyers and Allen
Iverson of the 76ers must overcome conflicts with the management of
their respective teams, McNabb is on the verge of making
Philadelphia his city. He's already made the Eagles his team.
</P>
<P>
   ''He comes from a program where he was asked to be the leader of
the Syracuse football team. We've done the same thing,'' Eagles
coach Andy Reid said. ''I don't think that's a part that he
struggles with. He handles that in a humble manner, yet a forceful
manner in the huddle.''
</P>
<P>
   And the 23-year-old seems to thrive in that role.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt I was the leader from last year,'' McNabb said. ''Being
in the quarterback position, that comes with the tag. Knowing that,
you have to be prepared for everything you may be faced with, be
ready to suffer through adversity. When you do that, guys know
you're prepared, you're ready to go and they'll follow.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb sat patiently while Pederson began last season as the
starting quarterback. He stepped in during Week 10, and finished
with eight touchdowns, seven interceptions and a 60.1 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are irrelevant compared to the intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb was the first to arrive at the stadium and last to leave,
often taking films home to study. He showed a willingness to play
hurt, returning early from a knee injury to play a meaningless
season finale.
</P>
<P>
   And from Day One, he demonstrated remarkable character,
especially the way he handled the infamous Philly boo-birds on
draft day.
</P>
<P>
   ''You begin to win, people will begin to jump on the
bandwagon,'' McNabb said after getting a rude welcome from about 30
Eagles fans who went to New York to urge the team to draft running
back Ricky Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   After the season, McNabb continued to work hard. He spent most
of the offseason practicing with wideout Charles Johnson in
Phoenix. He attended all of the team's minicamps and showed up
early for training camp. His entire vacation consisted of only one
week -- a trip to Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   The extra work is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of full practices, McNabb connected with
Johnson on a broken play that appeared to have been designed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were on the same page. We free-lanced it and made something
happen,'' Johnson said. ''It seemed like an actual play. It looks
like a relationship is building.''
</P>
<P>
   As the relationships continue to build and the team continues to
improve, expectations in Philadelphia will only become greater.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans will be disappointed if the Eagles don't win eight
games this season. They won a total of eight games the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just worry about what I need to do and that's play
quarterback,'' McNabb said. ''I don't worry about how people feel,
where they think we may end up or what our record will be. Anytime
you get involved in that, you begin to lose focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, McNabb has greater expectations than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has very high expectations for himself,'' Reid said. ''I
don't think anybody's expectations are higher than what he expects
for himself. He won't downplay that. He expects to go out and play
good football and, from a coach's standpoint, you don't want it any
other way than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
