<HEADLINE> Jaguars' RT Leon Searcy Injured  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Jacksonville Jaguars right tackle Leon
Searcy could be out for the season after tearing a tendon above his
right knee during practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The injury came during one-on-one drills at the start of morning
practice at training camp. Searcy rode off the field on a cart,
clutching his right knee, wincing in pain. He'll need surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars said Searcy suffered a ''significant tear'' of the
quadriceps tendon. The team didn't say how long the ninth-year Pro
Bowl tackle will be out, but bad tears of the quadriceps can take
up to nine months to heal.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line is the last place the Jaguars can afford an
injury, and Searcy is the last guy the team expected to go down. He
has missed only two games since 1992 and only one since he joined
the Jaguars in 1996. The one game he missed in Jacksonville was due
to an infected thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a freak incident,'' said defensive lineman Renaldo
Wynn, who was working opposite Searcy when the injury occurred.
''You don't expect something like that to happen, especially with
the caliber player Leon is. You've just got to bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville came into camp without left tackle Tony Boselli,
who is finishing rehabilitation on the knee ligament he tore last
season. Last year's left guard, Ben Coleman, is now playing for San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   If the season were to start tomorrow, Coughlin said, the Jaguars
probably would start second-year player Anthony Cesario and rookie
Brad Meester -- neither of whom has taken an NFL snap -- and Steve
Ingram, a journeyman who has played in eight NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Another inexperienced lineman, Todd Fordham, is coming off a
knee injury suffered last preseason. Rookie Joe Chustz, a
fourth-round draft pick, also pulled up lame Monday, with an aching
lower back.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you've got two guys who can't work at a position, that's
where the injuries are going to come,'' Coughlin said. ''It's
inevitable, but that's what happens. You don't feel sorry for
yourself. You just keep on going.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will be difficult without Searcy, who protects
left-handed quarterback Mark Brunell's blind side and is widely
considered one of the best blockers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Many people feel if Boselli were not on the line with him, it
wouldn't have taken Searcy nine years to be voted to his first Pro
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's pretty darn important,'' Coughlin said. ''But hopefully,
it's not something we can't overcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
