<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2000 Seahawks Have Youthful Look  </HEADLINE>
By MARK JEWELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. (AP) -- One of coach Mike Holmgren's big tasks this
year is to temper the Seattle Seahawks' youthful exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   After going 9-7 in the regular season and making the playoffs in
Holmgren's first year in Seattle, the Seahawks lost or got rid of
several veterans and restocked with younger players, including nine
rookies from the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just seven players on the team's 88-man training camp
roster are 30 or older. Nearly all the rest were born in the decade
of disco and leisure suits.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of the team's four-week training camp Monday,
Holmgren said he will enlist the few experienced hands he has left
to help guide the youth movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I'm asking of the older guys is to play better than they
played last year. That's the first thing they have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''But if they have time, yeah, that's part of their
responsibility, too, is take the young guys along and teach them
how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward youth is most evident on the offensive line,
where veterans Kevin Glover, Brian Habib and Grant Williams were
all cut in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Competing to fill those vacancies will be first-round draft pick
Chris McIntosh, second-year player Floyd Wedderburn and third-year
man Todd Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks also are youthful at wide receiver, thanks in part
to Holmgren's trade of veteran Joey Galloway to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The team's new receiving corps includes veterans Sean Dawkins
and Derrick Mayes, along with second-year-player Karsten Bailey and
Darrell Jackson, a rookie out of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren is impressed with Bailey and Jackson early in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to stop calling them young guys,'' he said. ''They
are going to get their chance to play a lot in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they got off to a great start.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting quarterback Jon Kitna hopes he and his teammates can
avoid mixing up Bailey and Jackson, both of whom boast good hands
and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are two clones out there with Karsten Bailey and Darrell
Jackson,'' Kitna said. ''I told Karsten not to get offended if
someone calls you Darrell or vice versa, because they look exactly
alike out there and their jersey numbers are only one number apart
(Jackson 82, Bailey 83).''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna hopes Holmgren can work the same kind of magic he did at
Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992-98, the Holmgren-coached Packers built young talent
into a team that made two Super Bowl appearances -- winning once --
and compiled a 75-37 regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at Green Bay and how they built their team, it's
similar'' to the Seahawks,'' said Kitna, a fourth-year quarterback.
''They built it with young talent and surrounded it with a few
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ''They sustained greatness for a long period of time, whereas if
you try to fill every need in one year, you kind of fade in and
fade out.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think coach Holmgren is building a program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
