<HEADLINE> Denver's Schlereth Has 27th Surgery  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- As surgical patients go, Denver Broncos
lineman Mark Schlereth deserves more than a medical chart. His
history reads more like a medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, Schlereth is a scientific marvel, visiting the surgeon as
often as most people visit the dentist. He latest trip came Monday
when he had arthroscopic surgery to remove a bone chip in his left
knee.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure at the Steadman-Hawkins Clinic in Vail marked the
27th time Schlereth has undergone some type of surgery in his
12-year career with the Broncos and Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The left knee has received the most attention, surgically
repaired 13 times.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a great pain threshold, and most guys probably would
have been retired a number of years ago,'' Denver coach Mike
Shanahan said. ''I think the doctors said that it was the worst
knee that they've every seen. That gives you an idea of what kind
of pain he plays with.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlereth, one of Denver's most dependable -- if not durable --
offensive linemen, hyperextended his knee Friday and has not
practiced since. He is expected to be out at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With three Super Bowl rings, it would be understandable if
Schlereth decided to call it a career, but he seemed determined to
play out the final year of his contract despite operations on his
knees, elbows, eyes and back.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all think about whether we want to come back or not,''
Broncos lineman David Diaz-Infante said. ''It's not easy to do,
especially with what he's been through. Mark has made a commitment
to people and he likes to honor those.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlereth deserves a Medal of Honor for his dedication and
perseverance. In 1998, he had arthroscopic surgery on his left knee
and was back in the starting lineup 13 days later. Because the
Broncos had a bye week, he did not miss a game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the big question mark is, 'Can he keep on coming back
and play at the same level?' We're hoping he can,'' Shanahan said.
''But if he can't, someone will have to step up and play in his
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   With Schlereth sidelined, second-year lineman Lennie Friedman
has filled his spot at left guard. Friedman is returning from a
torn anterior cruciate ligament his left knee, leaving him 26
surgeries behind Schlereth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there are many warriors like Mark Schlereth,''
Friedman said. ''I think he's a unique man and that's why he's as
good as he has been in the NFL. He's just an unbelievable
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Friedman's injury came during the first week of training
camp last July, he was able to gain some experience in the
offseason by playing for the Barcelona Dragons in NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, Denver's second-round draft pick in 1999, also spent
his spare time learning the Broncos' offense and watching veteran
linemen Schlereth, Dan Neil and Tony Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest thing was to go to meetings last year and pick up
as much of the offense as I can,'' Friedman said, ''so when I came
here it wasn't like learning everything all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Schlereth's experience and knowledge, missing two
weeks should not be a problem. Shanahan said staying in shape is
the biggest concern, and he joked that the latest surgery was
preordained.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is part of two-a-days for him,'' Shanahan said. ''I
honestly think he did it on purpose to be with his family for a
couple days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 1946 </TRAILER>
