<HEADLINE> Larry Ellison Finishes Yacht Race  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACKINAC ISLAND, Mich. (AP) -- Larry Ellison and his Maxi 78
Sayonara completed the Chicago-to-Mackinac yacht race Monday in 41
hours and 17 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That was good enough to take the Mac Race's First-to-Finish
honors in the Performance Handicapped Racing Federation. Last year,
Ellison was two minutes and four seconds short of the race's
fastest time of 25 hours, 50 minutes and 44 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Others finishing Monday in the PHRF division were the Zephyrus
IV and Magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Mongoose won First-To-Finish honors in the One Design division.
The yacht, skippered by Robert Sailelli, arrived at Mackinac Island
at 1:58 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Penny Beatty of the Chicago Yacht Club said a
calm wind turned racing yachts into ''bobbing corks'' a few short
miles from the finish line of the 330-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no wind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 a.m., race officials hadn't heard from Sayonara, she said,
but Ellison and Sayonara rolled past the finish line at 8:17 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Race officials also had a tough time tracking the boats Sunday
night because the island lost power, she said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 sailors set out Saturday in more than 300 boats
in the 93rd running of the race. The course runs from the shores of
Chicago northward through Lake Michigan, under the Mackinac Bridge
and into Lake Huron, ending at Mackinac Island.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more prominent racers include singer Bob Seger and
millionaire adventurer Steve Fossett, a catamaran racer.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett holds the race's multihull race record -- 18 hours, 50
minutes, 32 seconds -- set in 1998. Fossett is also known for
intercontinental hot-air balloon journeys.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: To track the boats:
http://www.sailnet.com/chicagomackinac/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
