<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates Urge Constitution Change  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Claiming the Constitution makes them
second-class citizens, foreign-born Americans and their advocates
urged a congressional subcommittee to allow them to run for
president after being U.S. citizens for 20 years instead of banning
them completely.
</P>
<P>
   ''Otherwise, millions of naturalized Americans will continue to
be victims of discrimination,'' said Raimundo Delgado, a teacher
from New Bedford, Mass., who became an American citizen after
leaving Sao Miguel in the Azores. ''All naturalized Americans
should have full civil rights under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution requires presidential candidates to be
''natural-born.'' Naturalized Americans are disqualified from the
nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   However, at least one foreign-born American told the House
Judiciary constitutional subcommittee that a change would be a bad
idea. ''To be able to run for president is not a right,'' said
Balint Vazsonyi, director of the Center for the American Founding.
</P>
<P>
   Vazsonyi, who became an American citizen after leaving Hungary,
said he believes that Americans have ''a unique brand of tolerance,
a balanced temperament and a natural goodwill toward the world''
that takes immigrants at least a generation to develop. He also
said he thought it unreasonable to expect immigrants to fully
understand the American ''Rule of Law.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Again, it is a miracle that so many immigrants are able to
operate within the American system of laws, contracts and
agreements on a handshake,'' he said. ''On the other hand, to
expect that someone who did not grow up with any of that could be
the guardian of our legal system is unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional amendment to change the presidential
requirement from a ''natural-born'' American to a person who has
been an American citizen for 20 years is unlikely to pass this
year, given the limited time left in the congressional session,
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is HJ Res. 88.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Judiciary constitutional subcommittee:
http://www.house.gov/judiciary/2.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
