<HEADLINE> Indictments filed against 15 in Central Park attacks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Manhattan prosecutors filed indictments Monday
against 15 men who have been accused of attacking - and in some
cases sexually abusing - women in Central Park after last month's
Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury charged the 15 defendants variously with riot,
sex abuse, assault and robbery. Most are accused of dousing women
with water and groping their buttocks and breasts on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Bernard Fried scheduled Sept. 6 as
the next court date for 12 of the defendants, and next Monday as
the date for three others.
</P>
<P>
   Several defense lawyers told Fried they needed time to review
more than 40 videotapes of the park attacks being turned over by
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Five jailed defendants asked for reduced bail Monday and Fried
lowered bail for four of them with the prosecutors' consent.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 27 defendants have been charged and are being
prosecuted as adults. Of those 27, 15 have been indicted. Felony
complaints have been filed against 10 others and misdemeanor
charges are pending against two more.
</P>
<P>
   At least 17 other ''John Doe'' defendants are being sought, the
district attorney's office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Second-degree assault and first-degree sex abuse are punishable
by up to seven years in prison; first-degree riot is punishable by
up to four years. The few who were charged with second-degree
robbery for allegedly snatching purses during the attacks face up
to 15 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Some suspects in the case were released without bail after
preliminary investigations failed to show definitely that the
defendants were involved in the attacks on the women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
