<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge grants probation to three Trumbull wrestlers in hazing abuse case </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - Three Trumbull High School wrestlers
accused in a brutal hazing ritual were granted a special form of
probation Monday that may clear their criminal records in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old victim, who was hogtied, sodomized with a
plastic knife and slammed against a wall in several incidents
between December and February, did not contest the probation for
his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Gerard Esposito ordered the three teen-age
boys each to pay $2,500 toward the victim's medical expenses. He
also sentenced them to 300 hours of community service apiece and
ordered them to undergo psychiatric evaluations and counseling as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   If the boys follow the terms of their probation and stay out of
trouble for two years, their records could be wiped clean.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what was going through your heads, but you've got
two years to earn yourselves a dismissal. Take advantage of that,''
Esposito said.
</P>
<P>
   Former wrestling team co-captains Daniel Rocco Scinto, 19, and
Jeremy Maxwell Dommu, 18, and teammate Christopher Ricci, 16,
apologized in court to the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry this ever happened,'' Scinto told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who has not been identified publicly, is a special
education student who suffers from attention deficit disorder and a
hyperactivity condition.
</P>
<P>
   The victim did not appear in court, but his lawyer, Howard
Klebanoff, said he expects to file civil lawsuits, possibly against
the Trumbull public schools and the assailants.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a family that is seeking vengeance. It's a family
that seeks justice,'' Klebanoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the wrestlers said their clients also endured hazing
to get on to the wrestling team, such as having their heads shaved
or being hung on towel hooks by their underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ''This kind of activity has been going on at Trumbull High
School for years,'' said Andrew Bowman, the lawyer for Dommu.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci's lawyer, Salvatore DePiano, said such hazing went on with
the acquiescence of school authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you wanted to be on the wrestling team, you had to go
through the hazing,'' DePiano said.
</P>
<P>
   School leaders have said such activity is prohibited in the
student conduct policy, which forbids intimidation, harassment or
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State's Attorney Peggy Kelley opposed the probation,
saying the charges were much too serious to warrant probation.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley described the case as ''one of the most offensive cases I
have ever prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   Scinto was charged with unlawful restraint and third-degree
assault. Dommu was charged with unlawful restraint and reckless
endangerment, and Ricci was charged with unlawful restraint and
attempted assault.
</P>
<P>
   In all, eight members of the wrestling team were charged in the
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The cases of five wrestlers have been resolved in juvenile
court. Three of them served a week in the juvenile detention
center.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the accused wrestlers were suspended for 10 days and
then expelled from school, and an eighth team member was suspended
for two days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman creates new traffic offense to help municipal prosecutors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman signed into law
Monday a measure that creates a new traffic offense and clarifies
the rules that allow municipal prosecutors to accept plea bargain
deals.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the state's Administrative Office of the Courts said
municipal court judges should no longer accept plea deals when the
facts don't fit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Many claimed that would end plea bargains and clog dockets at
local courts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill signed by Whitman creates a new traffic violation for
drivers who operate vehicles ''in an unsafe manner likely to
endanger person or property.'' Guilty drivers are not charged
penalty points in first or second offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who supported the bill said it will allow municipal
prosecutors and courts the flexibility to allow plea bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ''The municipal courts should not be placed in administrative
straitjackets that restrict rationality and compromise,''
Assemblyman Christopher Bateman, R-Somerset said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Plea bargains are a ''workable and successful practice,'' said
Assemblyman Neil Cohen, D-Union.
</P>
<P>
   The law is designed to help prosecutors and ''speed the flow of
traffic cases through the system,'' state Sen. Anthony Bucco,
R-Morris, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers will also benefit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation gives drivers who have made a mistake a
second chance. It gives them the opportunity to plead to this
violation, thus avoiding points, as long as they aren't habitual
offenders,'' Bucco said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2005 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuomo settlement with Puerto Rican authority under scrutiny  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - To settle a lawsuit over housing funds, the
Department of Housing and Urban Development agreed to pay $130
million to the Puerto Rican Housing Authority, even though the
agency faces corruption allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Now some Republicans are questioning why money is going to an
agency under federal investigation and hinted HUD Secretary Andrew
Cuomo may be cozying up to New York state's large Puerto Rican
constituency in advance of a possible run for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is just a whole raft of questions about alleged criminal
activity (in the housing authority) that I find very troubling and
make me wonder why HUD would do this,'' Sen. Christopher Bond,
R-Mo., said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican housing officials alleged HUD's allocation formula
has consistently shortchanged their administration. They first
filed a complaint in 1975, then a lawsuit in 1996 seeking $500
million.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials denied Cuomo's political aspirations were a factor
in settling the case. HUD spokesman Leland Jones said Cuomo agreed
the funding formula was unfair and wanted a settlement that was
fair to taxpayers and the Puerto Rican authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a landlord violates the law, do tenants get evicted? Of
course not. Then why should the people of Puerto Rico be denied
their fair share of funding because of the wrongdoing of others?''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo traveled to San Juan to announce the settlement on June 6,
four days before the Puerto Rican Parade in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement disturbed HUD Inspector General Susan Gaffney,
who sent a rare ''seven-day letter'' to Cuomo blasting the deal.
Such a letter requires a response to Congress within seven working
days.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney, an appointee of President Clinton who spars frequently
with Cuomo, criticized HUD's ''failure to stop flagrant fraud,
waste and abuse'' in the Puerto Rican housing administration. She
said HUD should have appointed an independent third party to handle
the authority's checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   In HUD's response, Deputy Secretary Saul Ramirez chastised
Gaffney, saying she had never made such a recommendation before and
that her use of a seven-day letter was inappropriate
</P>
<P>
   Bond, chairman of the committee that oversees HUD and a frequent
critic of Cuomo, fired off another letter to Cuomo on July 18
asking for additional documents on the housing authority and proof
that the Department of Justice had signed off on the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials say they received Justice approval and Justice
spokeswoman Kris Watney confirmed that on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption probe at the Puerto Rican authority is being
conducted by the HUD Inspector General's Office and the FBI.
According to a June 9 internal memo by Emil Schuster of the HUD
Inspector General's Office, the probes so far have resulted in 10
indictments and nine guilty pleas. Additional indictments are
expected, according to Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   The Puerto Rican Public Housing Administration is HUD's second
largest, trailing only New York City.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Department of Housing and Urban Development site:
http://www.hud.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2006 </TRAILER>
