<DOCNO> APW20000724.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio takes in prescription drug money in days following crucial vote </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio raked in thousands of dollars
for his U.S. Senate bid against Hillary Rodham Clinton from the
pharmaceutical industry in the days surrounding his vote for a GOP
prescription plan favored by the drug industry, according to
campaign finance records.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island Republican took in a total of $29,250 from
pharmaceutical companies and their executives in the two weeks
before and the day after the prescription drug vote June 29,
financial filings show.
</P>
<P>
   Political action committees for pharmaceutical giants Pfizer,
Glaxo Wellcome and Schering Plough each chipped in $5,000 apiece.
The GOP prescription measure passed by a close and mostly
party-line vote, 217-214.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick Lazio voted with the drug industry and then took their
cash. Once again Rick Lazio has sided with the special interests
over the needs of New York's seniors,'' Clinton spokesman Howard
Wolfson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lazio camp scoffed at that and noted the pharmaceutical
contributions were a tiny percentage of the $4.96 million he has
raised since entering the race in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only special interest that Rick listens to are the
interests of individual New Yorkers,'' Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Cooperstown Monday Lazio said the plan he
supported ''is going to be best for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has threatened to veto the GOP prescription
plan, which is opposed by most Democrats and some consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan would extend drug coverage through
government-subsidized policies sold by private insurers who would
participate voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Democrats are advocating a costlier alternative: a
uniform, government-run prescription drug benefit, offered to all
39 million elderly and disabled Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry is worried that if the government
runs the prescription program it will limit what they can charge
for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the pharmaceutical industry said they were
opposed to the government's ''one-size fits all approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We much prefer the plan that passed the House,'' Jeff Trewhitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Glaxo Wellcome, also said the money was not
given to Lazio to influence his position on the prescription vote.
Tom Fuldner said the money was based on an overall assessment of
the New York race and Lazio's record.
</P>
<P>
   ''We gave him money because we thought he would represent our
interests and would be like-minded,'' Fuldner said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio missed a recent vote on another measure opposed by the
drug industry. On July 10, the House voted to prevent the
government from discouraging the purchase of drugs in Canada or
other countries where they are cheaper than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the measure 363-12 as an amendment to the
Food and Drug Administration appropriations bill. It prevents the
agency from enforcing an importation ban on drugs, so long as they
are for personal use. Lazio was one of 66 members who missed the
House vote.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, the first lady has called for the
importation of cheaper drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on Monday, the moderate Republican Leadership Council,
which counts Gov. George Pataki among its leadership, released a
television advertisement that used the words of President Clinton
to link Lazio and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat Lazio
and the first lady are battling to replace. The 30-second spot
relies on footage of the president thanking Moynihan, Lazio and
others at a December ceremony for their work on legislation to help
disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her husband said it first ... We're following his lead,'' said
Mark Miller, executive director of the RLC.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is the second trotted out by the RLC to help boost
Lazio's candidacy. Miller said the group expects to spend $1
million between now and Labor Day on such advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan spokesman Tony Bullock criticized the spot, stressing
that Moynihan knew nothing of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly their intent is to deceive the viewer into believing
that the senator worked closely with Congressman Lazio on this
legislation and that he supports him for the Senate, neither of
which is true,'' Bullock said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2007 </TRAILER>
