<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Butler Fights For Job  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- LeRoy Butler is fighting for his job for
the first time in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Butler is the longest-tenured member of the Green Bay Packers
and a fixture in their defensive secondary for a decade. The
three-time All-Pro was a team leader on Green Bay's Super Bowl
teams and was considered the league's best blitzing safety for
years.
</P>
<P>
   But a subpar 1999 season has Butler hearing footsteps downfield.
In particular, brash second-year pro Antuan Edwards has declared
his intention to take either Butler's starting spot or that of
safety Darren Sharper.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm putting more pressure on myself than anyone else can put
on me,'' Butler said. ''I'm just looking forward to mixing it up
out there. May the best man win, that's my attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last season, there was no question Butler was the best
man. He said his performance last year -- two interceptions and just
one sack, both his lowest totals since 1992 -- was more due to his
role in former defensive coordinator Emmitt Thomas' scheme than to
a dropoff in his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the Packers' first-round pick a year ago, doesn't want
to wait for Butler's decline. He entered training camp determined
to become a starter, and has upped his physical play during the
first week of workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Even Butler's Pro Bowl resume and four-year contract extension
last season, which pays him $3.165 million this year, don't scare
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in here with a good attitude right now, and hopefully by
the end of this camp, I'll be No. 1,'' Edwards said. ''I'm going to
come out here and work as hard as I can. I'll be sitting on top by
the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' progress as a rookie was slowed by a foot injury that
didn't heal until shortly before the preseason. Though he played
extensively at cornerback and as an extra defensive back in passing
situations, he struggled to find his stride.
</P>
<P>
   He was also overshadowed by third-round pick Mike McKenzie, who
wowed coaches and unseated Craig Newsome as one of the Packers'
starting cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   With Tyrone Williams and McKenzie now entrenched at the
cornerback spots, the Packers moved Edwards back to safety -- his
position at Clemson -- during minicamps. Edwards said he doesn't
care where he plays -- as long as he plays a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's frustrating, really. I know I'm athletic enough and good
enough and smart enough to come out here and play,'' Edwards said.
''I just have to come out here and do what I have to do and
hopefully by the end of this camp I'll be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharper was the Packers' leading tackler last year, but was
criticized for a lack of physical play. He reported to camp in top
shape and has looked good in the first week of workouts, leading to
speculation that the starting battle will be between Edwards and
Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Ed Donatell's scheme requires one safety --
usually Sharper in early workouts -- to play up on the eight-man
front, while the other remains in the secondary. The defense also
frequently uses five and six defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   With so much responsibility being placed on the safeties in
Donatell's defense, neither Butler nor Edwards is likely to spend
much time on the sidelines. Coach Mike Sherman said a decision
won't be made on his starting safeties until the regular season
begins.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can feel a real sense of urgency around this position this
year,'' Sharper said. ''Everybody wants to learn the defense and
improve. I think it's making us a hungry team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: West Nile should be ''wake up call'' to medical community  </HEADLINE>
By PAT EATON-ROBB
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Citing a congressional report critical of
the handling of a mosquito virus, U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman on
Monday called for an improved federal response to outbreaks of
infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which concludes an eight-month investigation by the
Democratic staff of the Governmental Affairs Committee, said last
summer's outbreak of the West Nile-like strain of encephalitis
exposed the nation's vulnerability to emerging infectious disease.
The outbreak should serve as a ''wake up call,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is serious and we ought to take it seriously,'' said
Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat who is the ranking minority
member on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The report proposes a unified federal West Nile Virus response
plan, closer cooperation between experts in the fields of human and
animal health and an assessment of state's preparedness to deal
with the mosquito-borne disease. It also urges accelerated research
into a West Nile virus vaccine and a national web site to keep the
public and media informed.
</P>
<P>
   The report criticizes the way the Centers for Disease Control
responded to the outbreak that resulted in the deaths of seven
people in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, it faults the CDC for having ''tunnel vision''
after an initial diagnosis in humans blamed their illness on the
St. Louis version of the encephalitis virus.
</P>
<P>
   Indicators, including a massive die-off of birds in the area,
should have alerted health officials that something else was going
on, the report says. But a diagnosis of St. Louis encephalitis
''colored CDC's thinking for several weeks,'' and delayed a correct
diagnosis, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two diseases require the same prevention and control
measures, no harm was done, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   ''CDC failed to expect the unexpected,'' the report states.
''West Nile provided the wake up call. The next outbreak of an
infectious disease, whether naturally occurring or deliberately
inflicted, may not be so forgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement Monday, the CDC said the report
emphasizes the critical challenges the country faces regarding
emerging infectious diseases and said the recommendations in the
report can help clarify the importance of strong partnerships among
local, state and federal health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''As noted in the report, CDC has made significant progress in
addresing many of the recommendations. CDC takes seriously its
leadership role in preparing for emerging infectious disease
outbreaks and continues to work to keep Americans safe and
healthy,'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that while the CDC and others were
investigating human illness, animal health experts were doing a
separate investigation into the deaths of birds and horses.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cultural and communication divides between the worlds of
human disease and animal disease exacerbated the situation, a state
of affairs that must be righted,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   But the main emphasis of the report is on the improvement of the
public health infrastructure, and the establishment of disease
surveillance and reporting networks to better respond to any future
infectious disease crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That would include any bioterrorist attack, to which the report
says the West Nile outbreak shows the U.S. may be vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is widespread agreement that the next emerging or
re-emerging disease that lands on our shores may be even more
challenging than West Nile has proved to be, especially if it can
readily be spread from person to person, as diseases like flu and
small pox are,'' the report concludes. ''When - not if - such an
event occurs, there will be little margin for error in identifying
and responding to the disease.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2007 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
