<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional review sought for truck lane to Canada  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. - The board that makes long-range
transportation plans for Western New York has been asked to review
plans for a new truck lane to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Paul A. Dyster says he wants the Greater
Buffalo-Niagara Regional Transportation Council's take on a plan to
add two trucks-only lanes to the existing railroad track on the
upper deck of the Whirlpool Bridge. The plan was proposed on June
16 by the Niagara Falls Bridge Commission as a way with dealing
with increasingly crowded border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   Dyster said the City Council, which has passed a resolution
expressing concern about the proposal, is being rushed by claims
the project can be implemented in two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has put the Council under considerable pressure,'' Dyster
complained in a letter to state Transportation Commissioner Joseph
H. Boardman. ''We are, in short, being asked to make a decision
with very important long-term consequences in a pressure-cooker
atmosphere, with the implication that it is only our approval that
is holding up the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border traffic is expected to double within the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If some things aren't done, we're going to have problems the
likes of which we've never seen on this frontier,'' Bridge
Commission General Manager Allen Gandell said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Niagara County Industrial Development Agency and
the Niagara County Legislature Public Works Committee have approved
a request for $1 million from the Federal Highway Administration
for a study on transportation issues along Niagara County's
international border.
</P>
<P>
   The request, which failed last year due to late submission, is
currently being screened by the state Department of Transportation
in Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2009 </TRAILER>
