<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carolina Signs DL Eric Swann  </HEADLINE>
By JENNA FRYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) -- Defensive tackle Eric Swann followed
Reggie White to Carolina, signing a one-year deal with the Panthers
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, a 10-year veteran, was released by the Arizona Cardinals
two weeks ago and had been shopping himself around to interested
teams. The Jacksonville Jaguars and Denver Broncos made Swann
guaranteed offers, but he held out for the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The native of Swann Station, N.C., wanted to play in his home
state and with White, who signed with Carolina on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very, very happy,'' Swann's agent, Steve Zucker, said.
''Once Reggie went there, he said this is an opportunity to play
with him and he turned down two guaranteed deals that were
considerably larger than what we agreed to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is for one year and worth about the league minimum of
$440,000 for veterans, Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Swann was so anxious to join the Panthers, Zucker said, he
turned down the team's offer to send a plane to pick him up on
Tuesday and is instead taking a flight from Phoenix to make it in
time for practice Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''He can't wait to get there,'' Zucker said. ''This is where he
wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Swann is just the latest move by Carolina coach
George Seifert to overhaul his defense. The Panthers ranked 26th in
the league last year, but Seifert has since signed Chuck Smith from
Atlanta, Jay Williams from St. Louis and most recently White.
</P>
<P>
   White, the NFL's career sacks leader, came out of retirement to
join Carolina. Once he did that, Swann was sure he wanted to be
with the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, 29, played in the 1995 Pro Bowl with White and has been
bugging Zucker to reunite him ever since, Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The two players own property adjacent to each other outside of
Charlotte and both are building their permanent homes there.
</P>
<P>
   Like White, Swann will almost surely be used as a situational
player for 25-30 plays a game because of questions about his
durability.
</P>
<P>
   Swann has arthritic knees. He has undergone seven knee
operations over his career and missed 18 of 34 games the last two
seasons with the Cardinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 2018 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000724.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki heads to Maine for vacation  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki, one of several
Republicans who was thought to have been under consideration by
George W. Bush as a possible presidential running mate, headed to
Maine on Monday for a few days of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Republican, before word came out Monday evening
that former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney was Bush's choice, said
nothing should be read into the decision to spend a few days on the
Maine coast, north of former President Bush's Kennebunkport summer
home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had it planned for months,'' Pataki said Monday before
leaving for Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Portland later Monday evening, Pataki refused to
answer any questions.
</P>
<P>
   Most attention in recent days had centered on Cheney as Bush's
possible pick for vice president. Cheney, who had headed up the
Texas governor's search for a running mate, left Washington for
Texas on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was to make the announcement about his choice of Cheney on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush has not told me who he's choosing, but certainly
Cheney would be an outstanding choice if that in fact is the
choice,'' Pataki said in a telephone interview early Monday
afternoon before heading to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly there is a strong sense that Secretary Cheney would
be an outstanding choice ... Cheney does have that record of
government service, record of leadership in a very difficult time
during the Gulf War,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York governor refused to say if he had spoken to Bush in
the last several days.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I have or haven't, I'm not going to tell anybody,'' Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he would be returning to New York on Thursday,
although he said his wife Libby and children would be spending
longer in Maine. The governor is a delegate to next week's
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokeswoman Zenia Mucha said the Patakis would be
vacationing in New Harbor with Libby Pataki's sister and her
family. The Maine coastal village is north of Boothbay Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to be right where Libby's father grew up,'' Pataki
said. ''It's where we went on our honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said several of his wife's relatives still live in the
area where they will be vacationing, an island that her father once
owned near New Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is Libby's family thing and she's always wanted to show
our kids where her father lived,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki refused to give the name of the island they would be on.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to say because some of the more obnoxious press
might track us down,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
