<HEADLINE> Two indicted in 1994 New Jersey murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Two men were indicted Monday on federal
racketeering charges relating to the 1994 murders of three people
in Jersey City, N.J., and other acts of violence in New York and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan returned the
indictment against Lin Long Qun, 29, and Dong Qi Ming, 31, after
hearing evidence that they committed numerous acts of violence,
including the murders.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accused the men of killing Huang Yong Ting, Jiang
Ai Qin and Lin Yu in August 1994 in a basement apartment on Wayne
Street in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   It said the defendants at the time were members of a Chinese
alien-smuggling gang and committed the murders to boost their
standing.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said the gang also was responsible for several
kidnappings of Chinese illegal aliens shortly after their arrival
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Qun and Ming also were accused of participating in the robbery
of a restaurant owner in Downingtown, Pa., in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Qun is currently incarcerated at the State Correctional Center
in Bellefonte, Pa., where he was serving a 15-year to 40-year
prison term following his conviction on a robbery charge.
</P>
<P>
   Ming's lawyer did not immediately return a telephone message for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, both defendants face a maximum sentence of life in
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
