<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gypsy moth defoliation hits five-year high  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN MANNING
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) - Kept in check for the past several years, the
voracious gypsy moth caterpillar is making a resurgence in
Maryland's forests, chewing through any foliage that stands in its
way.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves on Maryland's trees are being stripped by gypsy moths
at the highest rate in the last five years. The nefarious invaders
defoliated 22,566 acres of the state's trees this spring, with most
of that acreage concentrated in western Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   And the damage is a sign that things could get worse, said
Robert Tichenor, head of the Forest Pest Management Section of the
Maryland Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have a bigger problem next year than we have
had in quite a few years,'' he said. ''This trend has been going on
for the past three or four years. How many more it is going to
continue is anybody's guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have seen a growing number of egg masses on tree
trunks over the past several years, Tichenor said, a harbinger of
future infestations.
</P>
<P>
   The devastation wreaked by the gypsy moths on Maryland's forests
ballooned to 133,000 acres in 1990, and hovered around 100,000
annually until 1995. But a combination of environmental controls
such as predators and parasites cut into gypsy moth populations
after 1995, reducing the damage to Maryland's trees.
</P>
<P>
   It was the failure of one of those controls - a fungus that is
lethal to the gypsy moth caterpillar - that contributed to the
population resurgence this year, Tichenor said. The fungus, which
feeds off the bodies of the caterpillars, did not appear this year
until the insects were fully grown and had already done significant
damage.
</P>
<P>
   In aerial surveys of Maryland's forests this spring, researchers
spotted numerous patches of trees with 50 percent or more of their
foliage gone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of seeing a nice thick carpet of green, you'll see
brownish areas that look as if it were a threadbare carpet,''
Tichenor said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't limited to Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania expects to record over 1 million defoliated acres
this year, and West Virginia already has counted 200,000 acres
affected by gypsy moths. New Jersey, which had 1,380 acres
defoliated last year, has recorded 130,000 acres invaded by
caterpillars this year. And Virginia reported its first defoliation
since 1995, with 71,000 acres affected.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy moths were introduced into North America in the mid-1800s
by a Massachusetts entrepreneur who hoped the cocoon spun by the
larval caterpillar would be an alternative to silk. While the
insect failed as a textile producer, it flourished on the abundant
supply of oak and other North American trees.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 150 years, the gypsy moth began a slow march
through New England and the mid-Atlantic region. Since the female
does not fly, the gypsy moth spreads only about 10-15 miles per
year, Tichenor said.
</P>
<P>
   But that immobility also means gypsy moths can reach critical
limits in infested areas, causing often-fatal damage to trees. The
caterpillars destroy leaves in the spring, meaning the tree has to
tap into its energy reserves to grow new foliage. The weakened
trees are then susceptible to disease and drought.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners concerned about backyard trees should knock off egg
patches to curb future damage, Tichenor said. The state also has
been spraying insecticides in selected areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew it was coming, but we didn't quite expect it to come
all of a sudden like it did this year,'' Tichenor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-24-00 2030 </TRAILER>
