<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flowers Makes Debut At Bills Camp  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFORD, N.Y. (AP) -- Four days late, rookie defensive end Erik
Flowers felt like all eyes were on him Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of reminds you of being a little five-year-old going
to kindergarten class, but being late and everybody's watching you
as you walk through the door,'' Flowers said after making his debut
at Buffalo Bills training camp. ''I was a little nervous during the
beginning of the drills. But things started to fit in a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, selected 26th overall from Arizona State in April's NFL
draft, finally hit the field at St. John Fisher College after
signing a five-year contract Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Monetary terms were not disclosed, but it's believed the deal is
worth between $5.5 million and $6 million, plus a signing bonus of
more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was pretty confident that it was going to get done in the
first week,'' Flowers said. ''My agent knows these guys. (He's)
done tons of contracts with them. I knew it was going to get done
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came when Flowers' agent, Arizona-based Eric
Metz, flew to Rochester over the weekend to personally handle the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came not a moment too soon for the Bills, who are
relying on Flowers to play an important role in helping fill Bruce
Smith's shoes on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers will get plenty of playing time in place of Marcellus
Wiley, who needs at least two more weeks to recover from back
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Wade Phillips raised concerns that the holdout could limit
Flowers' development. Now Phillips is expecting to see the player
that impressed him at the Bills' previous minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ''After seeing him in the June camp, I felt like he was going to
play an important role on this team,'' Phillips said. ''He's an
awfully good-looking football player. It didn't matter who was here
or who wasn't here. From what I've seen so far, I think he's going
to be playing on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bills defensive coordinator Ted Cottrell said Flowers hasn't
missed much.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing he missed is a lot of pizza and stuff at
night,'' Cottrell said. ''The practices that he missed, I don't
think they're going to hurt him at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a few tries, but Flowers did make a big impact during
the morning session.
</P>
<P>
   In 1-on-1 pass rush drills, rookie offensive tackle Jon Carman
appeared to have the better of Flowers. Then, suddenly, Carman
found himself lying face-first on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Using his highly touted speed and underrated strength, Flowers
got around Carman with a clever half-spin move and, with his right
arm, shoved the tackle over.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the play before that, Jon blocked me. He had me beat,''
Flowers said. ''I went back and asked the guys, 'What am I doing
wrong?' And they said, 'You're not trying to bend the corner,
you're still hesitant.' And I guess I just went out there and
played.''
</P>
<P>
   An impressed Carman said: ''He looks great. Very quick. His
upper body -- he's a very strong guy. You really got to hunker down
to hold on to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers' linemates welcomed his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ''By the end of this week, he'll be up to speed with the rest of
the team,'' veteran defensive end Phil Hansen said. ''I know he's a
rookie, but he's a smart kid. He's big, strong, he's got all the
tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Added backup lineman Shawn Price: ''He's going to catch up
quickly. ... He knows his plays, it's just a matter of getting his
legs underneath him, enduring the pounding and all that. He'll be
fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
