<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Slows Brazil Oil Spill Cleanup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Rains complicated the cleanup of a
major oil spill in southern Brazil over the weekend, but workers
prevented oil trapped near a refinery from leaking into a river,
oil company officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup crews have removed all but 5,000 gallons of oil from the
Iguacu River, contaminated when more than 1 million gallons spewed
from a burst pipeline last week at the Getulio Vargas refinery,
federal oil giant Petrobras said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 gallons of oil remained on the refinery
grounds, Petrobras said. Over the weekend, workers built four
concrete dikes to prevent rains from washing oil into a tributary
of the Iguacu, which flows across Parana state to world-famous
Iguacu Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Rains hampered cleanup efforts at the river, as muddy roads
prevented the access of crews, trucks and other cleanup equipment,
Petrobras spokesman Luiz Antonio Magnani said.
</P>
<P>
   Around 100 animals coated in oil were found during the cleanup
and taken to a veterinary hospital in nearby Curitiba, the capital
of Parana state 435 miles southwest of Rio. Half of the animals
died, Petrobras said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rain-swollen current did not push the oil beyond
contention barriers, as environmentalists had feared. Samples of
river water taken Sunday at several points below the barriers were
not contaminated by the oil, according to Parana State's
Environmental Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Petrobras said that it would remove the remaining oil from the
polluted 27-mile stretch of the Iguacu River by Wednesday, then
cleanup efforts would turn to the oil still contained within the
refinery.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government on Monday fined Petrobras about $84
million and ordered the company to compensate riverside residents
for damages, local media reported. The Parana state government has
separately fined Petrobras $28 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
