<HEADLINE> Latest ad from Clinton campaign  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the newest ad from Hillary Rodham
Clinton's
Senate campaign, highlighting her interest in health issues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Clinton campaign adviser Mandy Grunwald and ''Team
Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Downstate.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: (Announcer) She's talking about health care, because
it's always been her cause.
</P>
<P>
   When her health care plan was defeated, she kept on fighting
step by step and made a difference. Mammograms covered by Medicare.
Longer hospital coverage for new mothers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Hillary will fight to provide health care access
to every child, for a real Patients' Bill of Rights and tax credits
to help those without coverage on the job. Who'll be a strong voice
for better health care?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary. Always has been, always will be.
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Clinton is pictured speaking with patients and doctors
in a hospital, and talking with people around the state. Many of
those pictured are elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on the screen are the words ''Mammograms covered by
Medicare,'' ''Longer hospital coverage for new mothers,'' ''Health
care access to every child,'' ''A real Patients' Bill of Rights,''
and ''Tax credits to help those without coverage on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: This commercial seeks to turn the defeat of the first
lady's health care reform plan into a credential that proves her
long-standing advocacy, and her willingness to keep fighting for a
cause. As in many of the other ads that have sought to recast her
cold, cerebral image, the first lady is portrayed here as friendly
and caring, and her last name is never mentioned. The viewer is on
a permanent first-name basis with ''Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's support for insurance coverage for a 48-hour
hospitalization after childbirth, and for expanded Medicare
coverage for mammograms, is real. The ad may, however, leave some
viewers with the false impression that the first lady was
responsible for these programs rather than having had a limited
role as an advocate, not a legislator.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   AdWatch analysis by Associated Press Writer Beth J. Harpaz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
