<HEADLINE> Vikings Sign First-Round Pick Hovan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- First-round draft choice Chris Hovan
signed with Minnesota on Monday, giving the Vikings all of their
players in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The All-American defensive lineman from Boston College, the 25th
overall pick in April, was expected to report to camp Monday night.
Hovan missed both practices Monday while his agents finished
negotiating his contract with Vikings officials.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of Hovan's contract were not announced, but the Saint Paul
Pioneer Press reported the deal was worth about $5 million over
five years, including a $3 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   With the retirement of Jerry Ball last week, Hovan -- who can
play end or tackle -- is expected to compete for a starting position
on the defensive line, which also lost Chris Doleman to retirement
and Duane Clemons to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Ball, Doleman and Clemons combined for 19 sacks last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' first three picks in the draft were defensive
linemen. Wake Forest's Fred Robbins and Miami's Michael Boireau
were taken in the second round.
</P>
