<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, July 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cheney Said To Be GOP VP Pick
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- George W. Bush has chosen former Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney to be his GOP vice presidential running mate. Two highly placed GOP
sources said Bush planned to make the offer tomorrow morning. Cheney, who played
a key role in the presidency of the Texas governor's father, has indicated he
would accept the offer to join the ticket. A Bush spokeswoman confirmed he had
made his pick, but added, ''He has not yet notified that individual or told
anyone else about his choice.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Talks Are Open-Ended
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- President Clinton will extend the Mideast summit talks
as long as there is ''a realistic chance'' he can forge a peace agreement
between Israel and the Palestinians, a White House spokesman said today. ''They
are trying to find areas of agreement. They have found some,'' Joe Lockhart
said. He indicated the summit was likely to continue at least through tomorrow
night. Overall, Lockhart said, ''there is no way of predicting how long this
will go.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Feds Probe Clinton's Money Ties
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal investigators looking into alleged fund-raising
abuses by Democrats questioned President Clinton extensively about his ties to
Indonesian businessman James Riady, dating back to his 1992 White House
campaign. In testimony released today, Clinton said he did not remember a 1992
limousine ride in which Riady purportedly pledged to funnel $1 million in
donations to his campaign.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Dead at Fla. Hostage Site
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A three-day standoff at a suburban Orlando home ended
today with the death of a hostage and the suicide of the murder suspect who
began the ordeal. Police said Jamie Dean Petron, 41, killed himself. The
hostage, Andrea Hall, 40, had been dead for several hours. Hall and four other
people were taken hostage Saturday after Petron wounded a sheriff's deputy. Two
children were released yesterday and two others were freed today by police,
shaken but unharmed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miller Appointed to U.S. Senate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Georgia's Democratic former governor Zell Miller was
appointed today to the late Republican Paul Coverdell's Senate seat and said he
will run for the remaining four years of the term in November. Gov. Roy Barnes,
a Democrat, officially announced the appointment, saying Miller, 68, was the
best-qualified person from either party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tobacco Case Moves To Federal Court
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- In a surprise move, the tobacco industry switched a landmark
Florida smokers' case and its record-breaking $145 billion verdict to federal
court today. Tobacco attorneys acted based on a motion filed on the day of the
punitive damage verdict by a union health care plan seeking to intervene. The
industry also filed a motion challenging the July 14 verdict and laying the
ground work for a state appeal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NY To Spray Central Park for Virus
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mosquitoes carrying the West Nile virus have been found in
Central Park, prompting officials to close the New York landmark tonight so they
can spray it with insecticides. ''The public should not have a great deal of
apprehension,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said. ''Go about your lives normally, but
for one night, stay out of the park.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More High School Dropouts Get GED
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With the economy demanding a more educated workforce, more
dropouts are obtaining GED high school equivalency diplomas, according to a
survey released today by the testing program. The half million GED recipients in
1999 remain, however, a tiny fraction of the more than 45 million Americans who
never finished high school. About one in seven high school diplomas issued each
year is a GED.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Internet Costs Much in Taxes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- States and localities will lose between $300 million and
$3.8 billion in tax revenue this year because of purchases over the Internet,
the General Accounting Office said today. The GAO, Congress' investigative arm,
said the wide disparity was due to the difficulty of documenting Internet sales.
Electronic retailers are not compelled to collect sales taxes from customers
unless goods are being sent to a state where the retailer has a store or other
physical presence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 48; Nasdaq Falls 113
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today after weaker-than-expected corporate
earnings reports overshadowed signs of moderating inflation. The Dow Jones
industrial average ended down 48.44 at 10,685.12. On the NYSE, losers led
gainers by a 3-to-2 margin. The Nasdaq was down 112.88 at 3,981.57.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arizona Wins Hall of Fame Game
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks rallied with six runs in
the eighth inning to beat the Cleveland Indians 12-7 today in the annual Hall of
Fame exhibition game at Doubleday Field. Arizona's Alex Cabrera hit a two-run
single for the decisive runs.
</P>
