<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Joe Clark To Seek House of Commons Seat
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Tory Leader Joe Clark will seek a seat in a Nova
Scotia byelection, joining rival Canadian Alliance Leader Stockwell
Day in an attempt to reach the House of Commons by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   MP Scott Brison will announce Tuesday that he is stepping aside
in the riding of Kings-Hants to allow Clark to run. The seat has
been a safe one for the Tories, held by the party in all but one
election since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are times when an opportunity arises to do something
that makes a big difference and this is one of those occasions,''
Brison said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe very strongly that ... Joe Clark belongs in the
House of Commons and I cannot apply pressure and demonstrate that
support without offering my seat -- to do otherwise would be
hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark became leader of the Progressive Conservatives in November
1998, but said he preferred to devote himself to fundraising and
policy development in the party rather than heading straight into
the Commons.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure began to mount for him to find a way into Parliament
early this year when the Reform party merged into the Canadian
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Alberta Gov't Releases Health-Care Clinic Draft Regulations
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- The Alberta government moved Monday to
put flesh on the bare bones of its private health-care legislation,
releasing draft regulations to govern how private clinics operate
within the publicly funded system.
</P>
<P>
   Several key elements of the law have been turned over to the
College of Physicians and Surgeons of Alberta, which sets the rules
for the practice of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Health Minister Gary Mar said the doctors' group will determine
what procedures will be carried out in private clinics and whether
patients can be kept overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the college says there cannot be any overnight stays
because they cannot safely be done in such facilities, that will
end the question,'' Mar told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   During the fractious debate on the bill this spring, Premier
Ralph Klein said Alberta's health-care system would allow private
clinics to do some surgeries requiring overnight stays.
</P>
<P>
   That shifted as widespread opposition to the bill -- both in
Alberta and across Canada -- mounted. Mar confirmed Monday overnight
stays are only a possibility that could be ruled out by the
college.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Victoria Bank Robbery Driver Found Guilty on Seven Charges
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- The driver of a getaway car in
a spectacular bank robbery in Victoria a year ago has been found
guilty of seven of nine charges, including attempted murder of a
police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Allan McCallum was arrested along with notorious bank robber
Stephen Reid last June.
</P>
<P>
   Reid is serving 18 years in prison for his part in the heist,
which was followed by a car chase and shots fired at police.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum, who was sporting curly hair reaching midway down his
back, stood motionless as he was found guilty of the attempted
murder of Victoria police officer Cpl. Bill Trudeau.
</P>
<P>
   Trudeau was forced to run his motorcycle off the road while in
pursuit of the pair after he came around a blind corner to find the
getaway car stopped and Reid leveling a rifle at his head.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said there was no doubt McCallum was aware of Reid's
intentions when he stopped the car, allowing his partner to get out
and aim the weapon at the approaching officer.
</P>
<P>
   McCallum was convicted of dangerous driving, having his face
masked, using a firearm to commit robbery and three counts of
discharging a firearm to prevent arrest. then out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Air Canada and Pilots Can't Agree on Mediator
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- After considering several possible mediators,
Air Canada and its pilots failed to agree Monday on who should help
settle their contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said Monday that travelers' vacation plans shouldn't
be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Labor Minister Claudette Bradshaw is now expected to
appoint a mediator to resolve the impasse, which has left
passengers fearing for weeks that pilots could walk off the job
after giving 72 hours notice.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Foster, a spokesman for the Air Canada Pilots
Association, said passengers will not immediately be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both Air Canada and the Air Canada Pilots Association have
agreed not to exercise their right to a strike or lockout while the
mediation process is ongoing,'' said Foster.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Canada spokeswoman echoed those reassurances.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the traveling public, it means that they can move forward
with their travel plans without any worries,'' said Nicole
Couture-Simard.
</P>
