<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Wounded in Mexico Police Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Attackers fired assault rifles at a police
station, wounding a police captain and two members of a family with
a barrage of bullets, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Rafael Hernandez Gutierrez was shot in the back during the
attack Sunday night, while Juan Carlos Garcia and his son were
grazed by bullets, police spokesman Victor Manuel Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Mexico City newspaper and a radio station reported
receiving anonymous calls saying the People's Revolutionary Armed
Forces, or FARP, was responsible for the attack, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, an air force captain, and his family were in a car in
front of the station, 15 miles outside Mexico City. His wife and
three other young children were cut from flying glass when the
bullets hit their car, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez was hospitalized in stable condition, authorities
said. The others were treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe six gunmen shot at the station from a nearby
hill. More than 120 police were scouring the area Monday but had
made no arrests by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The government has identified the FARP as one of five splinter
groups of the Popular Revolutionary Army, a Marxist guerrilla group
based in Guerrero state.
</P>
<P>
   In March, a small explosive went off at another federal police
station in the city, causing minor damage but no injuries. Shortly
afterward, a child was injured after he found another small
explosive planted outside that same station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
