<HEADLINE> The Seven Seas Wins at Hollywood  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- The Seven Seas rallied from far off the
pace to win Monday's $136,375 Estrapade Stakes by 1&AMP;frac34; lengths over
Keemoon on the closing day of Hollywood Park's 65-day Spring/Summer
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Seven Seas, ridden by Alex Solis and carrying 121 pounds,
covered 1&AMP;frac12; miles on turf in 2:27 1-5 and, as the 3-2 favorite, paid
$5, $3 and $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   The win was the fourth in nine lifetime starts for The Seven
Seas and was worth $81,825, raising the career earnings of the
4-year-old Kentucky-bred daughter of El Gran Senor to $229,972.
</P>
<P>
   ''They key with her is to wait until the last eighth of a mile
to make her run,'' Solis said. ''It's amazing, the turn of foot she
has. She just explodes the last part.''
</P>
<P>
   Keemoon, ridden by Kent Desormeaux and carrying 117 pounds,
crossed the finish line 2&AMP;frac12; lengths in front of Country Garden and
returned $6 and $4.
</P>
<P>
   Country Garden, ridden by Laffit Pincay Jr. and carrying 117
pounds, was 1&AMP;frac12; lengths ahead of Bienandanza at the wire and paid $3
to show.
</P>
<P>
   Following Bienandanza across the finish line in the fifth
running of the race for fillies and mares were Sweet Eternity,
Marie De Bayeux and Undressed. Gleefully was scratched.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Eternity, the 7-2 second-favorite, led most of the way
before fading.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Espinoza won the Hollywood Park jockey title -- his first
major championship -- with 62 victories, including one on closing
day. Corey Nakatani finished with 51 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughbred racing in Southern California now shifts to the San
Diego area, where Del Mar begins its 61st racing season Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting opening day of the 43-day meeting will be the
Oceanside Stakes for 3-year-olds, which will be run in split
divisions for the 13th straight year.
</P>
</TEXT>
