<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Gov't Pledges Voting Rights  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Top advisers to Mexico's president-elect said
Monday that one of their first priorities will be giving the vote
to Mexicans living abroad.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 million Mexicans live abroad, the vast majority in the
United States. They constitute about 14 percent of all Mexicans of
voting age, according to Mexico's independent Federal Electoral
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   All major political parties have long professed their desire to
let those Mexicans vote, and in 1996 Mexico's Congress unanimously
approved a law giving them the right to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress failed to approve a mechanism for such voting -- a
failure that opposition parties blamed on the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Vicente Fox won the presidency, ending the PRI's
71-year rule. Both Fox's National Action Party and the main leftist
opposition, the Democratic Revolutionary Party, repeatedly have
pledged to enable the vote abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties together now will have a collective majority in
both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it will happen. There will be voting abroad in the next
elections,'' one of Fox's top political advisers, Santiago Creel,
said Monday. ''We are in agreement (with Democratic Revolution)
that Mexicans be allowed to vote in the entire world.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists in the United States are still cautious about that
pledge. Many worry that the problems that have held up the voting
so far could continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''They promised it several years ago, but in politics promises
can be betrayed,'' said Felipe Aguirre, a voting-rights activist in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 million Mexicans in the United States, only an
estimated 1.5 million are registered voters. A voter-registration
drive in a foreign country with a widely dispersed population would
be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear who would be allowed to vote; the law is unclear,
for example, on whether Mexicans who become foreign citizens would
be allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Should people be able to vote if they've never been to Mexico?
If they don't have ties to Mexico? If they don't speak Spanish?''
asked Jorge Santibanez, president of the College of the Northern
Border in Tijuana. ''Maybe now there's a political will, but the
operational reality is not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems feasible that those 1&AMP;frac12; million with voting
credentials could vote,'' Santibanez said. ''But I see it as very
improbable that all 10 million Mexicans in the United States will
be voting in Mexican elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions about financing and organizing the vote beyond Mexican
borders also complicated the debate in Mexico's Congress. Mexican
election laws demand elaborate safeguards which would be
complicated to enforce elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the July 2 elections, Mexicans abroad were almost
disenfranchised. Only a few special polling places were set up
along the border -- which is a long way from Chicago or New York --
and almost all quickly ran out of their legally allotted 750
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Many PRI officials had been reluctant to see Mexicans abroad
voting because they overwhelmingly supported other parties. Many
fled Mexico because of the economic conditions they blamed on the
long-ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was the PRI that elected the first U.S. resident to
Mexico's Congress. Eddie Varon of Los Angeles won a
proportional-representation seat for the ruling party and will join
the lower house in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-24-00 2218 </TRAILER>
