<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dems attack VP selection  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN BREZOSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York Democrats were quick to attack
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's widely reported running mate choice as
a look back - to the days of George Bush Sr.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a return to the failed policies of his father,'' state
Democratic Party Chairwoman Judith Hope said Monday after hearing
news reports Bush had picked former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
as candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounds like his advisers wanted him to have an adult around
to help him,'' Hope said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, is seen as a bridge between Bush and his father, who
as president put Cheney in his Cabinet and promoted him for his
son's ticket. He was mentioned as a possible running mate for the
elder Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The six-term senator from Wyoming also served as chief of staff
for President Ford and was Pentagon chief during the Persian Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, he voted against Democrats on almost every social
issue, including abortion rights and gun control, earning a nearly
perfect rating from the American Conservative Union.
</P>
<P>
   He was likewise an ardent supporter of President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   With the news Monday night coming from everywhere but Bush
himself, Committee officials said they were reluctant to predict
how that choice would play with voters.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Party Chairman Bill Powers hailed Cheney, and
his record.
</P>
<P>
   ''A wise man and a wise choice,'' Powers said. ''He's been
tested. He's come through very well as chief of staff, congressman,
as secretary of defense in the Persian Gulf War. I think he'll do
very well in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who was himself on the short list of
possible running mates, likewise called Cheney an ''outstanding
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Cheney does have that record of government service, record of
leadership in a very difficult time during the Gulf War,'' Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two highly placed GOP sources said Bush planned to make the
offer Tuesday morning. Cheney has told associates he will accept
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
