<HEADLINE> Teen Pleads Innocent in Shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The 13-year-old boy accused of firing a gun in a
middle-school cafeteria pleaded innocent Monday to eight felony
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Warnock, who remains in juvenile detention, is suspected of
firing a .22-caliber pistol at the ceiling July 17 during summer
classes at Dimmitt Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt, and he allegedly fled when other students ran
away rather than obey his order to herd themselves on a stage. He
turned himself in the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Warnock was charged Friday with three counts of assault, three
counts of kidnapping, one count of unlawful possession of a firearm
by a minor and one count of possession of a stolen firearm. If
convicted, he could be held until age 21.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the King County prosecutor's office said that a
12-year-old boy arrested in the case would be released pending a
closer look at his role, if any, in the incident.
</P>
