<HEADLINE> Islanders Sign Top Pick DiPietro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- The New York Islanders signed Rick
DiPietro, the first goalie selected No. 1 in the NHL entry draft,
to a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   The team scheduled a news conference for Tuesday to announce the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations began shortly after the Islanders used the first
pick in last month's draft on the 18-year-old goalie from Boston
University. The team announced that a deal was completed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro, from Winthrop, Mass., was the top-ranked North
American goalie by NHL Central Scouting. He went 17-3-5 with a 2.50
goals-against average and a .909 save percentage last season. He
also set an NCAA record with 77 saves in one game.
</P>
<P>
   After just one year of college, DiPietro made himself available
for the draft and voided his remaining three years of eligibility.
The decision was made to avoid going into a goalie-heavy draft next
year.
</P>
<P>
   On draft day, New York made room for DiPietro by trading both of
their goalies from last season. Kevin Weekes was sent to the Tampa
Bay Lightning and Roberto Luongo went to the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Luongo held the distinction of being the highest selected goalie
ever when New York picked him No. 4 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro will conduct a private clinic for more than 20 young
goalies on Tuesday morning and then join Islanders co-owner Charles
Wang and general manager Mike Milbury to announce the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
