<DOCNO> APW20000724.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Summit in High Gear  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- Enmeshed in the tough details, President
Clinton will extend the Mideast summit talks as long as there is
''a realistic chance'' he can hammer out a peace agreement between
Israel and the Palestinians, his spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the two sides had been able to find some areas of
agreement in the first two weeks of talks, spokesman Joe Lockhart
said, ''They are trying to find areas of agreement. They have
probably found some.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman indicated, at the same time, that the summit was
likely to continue at least through Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton intended to go to Arkansas during the day to
attend a memorial service for Diane Blair, a University of Arkansas
political science professor and close friend, and return Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, Lockhart said, ''there is no way of predicting
how long this will go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Israeli camp, negotiator Ammon Lipkin-Shahak said he
could not give odds on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's either zero or 100 ... One can't know.'' he said. ''The
argument is not over decisions, but positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Duplicating the hands-on mediation of President Jimmy Carter at
Camp David 22 years ago, Clinton met with a mixed group of Israeli,
Palestinian and U.S. negotiators until after 5 a.m. and then got
together with them again for four hours after a few hours' sleep.
</P>
<P>
   At late afternoon, during a brief break in the talks, Lockhart
said the White House believed ''it's still constructive to continue
these sessions.'' Additional talks were scheduled Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   He described the talks as ''exhaustive and exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the talks might collide with the Republican
convention, which next week will nominate George W. Bush as the GOP
presidential candidate, Lockhart said, ''I don't think there's a
sense that those two things were going to collide. ... Governor
Bush has been properly supportive of the president so I don't think
on either side there's an attempt to play politics with this.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis said the talks were at a critical juncture. Top
negotiator Shlomo Ben-Ami told Israel's army radio Monday that
''the outcome ... will become finally or almost finally clear
during the next two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Back Sunday evening from economic talks in Japan, Clinton was
briefed by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on her weekend in
charge, met separately with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, had dinner with them and their
delegations and then began ''trying to work through the details''
with an array of negotiators, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held another round of detailed talks Monday with
negotiators -- not including Arafat and Barak -- making a ''rolling
assessment'' of whether the substance and atmosphere of the
discussions ''have the potential to lead to an agreement,'' his
spokesman said. Arafat and Clinton met for an hour in early
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Carter in 1978 took on much of the heavy detail work
at a 13-day summit with the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and
the late Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin that produced a
peace treaty the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's summit was in its 14th day Monday with no indication
Clinton was ready to call a halt. Guardedly upbeat, Lockhart said,
''As long as we are sitting here there is a prospect of
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Implying Clinton was going for broke -- an overall agreement
instead of a partial accord -- Lockhart said, ''To reach an
agreement, they need to work through each of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   None is more difficult than Jerusalem, which Arafat wants split
into Jewish and Palestinian parts, hoping to establish his capital
in the older part of the ancient and historically contested city.
Pope John Paul II proposed Sunday that it be made an international
city, a suggestion from which the White House kept its distance.
</P>
<P>
   Other core issues, all fraught with emotion and security
implications, include how much of the West Bank will be
relinquished by Israel, how many Palestinian refugees will be taken
in by the Jewish state, and how many Israeli Jews will remain on
the West Bank and in Gaza after Arafat turns the territories into a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the issue of Jonathan Pollard, an American
convicted and jailed for spying for Israel, was on the table,
Lockhart said, ''I'm not aware that it's come up in the context of
the discussions.'' He noted, however, that he knows of no time that
Clinton and Barak talked that Israel's request for his release was
not raised.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's willingness to make concessions far exceeding those of
his predecessors has weakened his political support at home. Three
political parties have quit his government and his foreign
minister, David Levy, declined to participate in the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''No prime minister has the right to make concessions over
Jerusalem,'' Ariel Sharon, the tough-minded former Likud foreign
minister, told Israel radio. ''Jerusalem is the birthright of the
Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, top Arafat aide Tayib Abdel Rahim said
Arafat stood ready to provide all faiths with access to Jerusalem's
holy sites -- as long as that was part of a sovereignty pact.
</P>
<P>
   ''The solution is very simple -- give full sovereignty of East
Jerusalem to a Palestinian state,'' Abdel Rahim, who is in frequent
contact with Arafat, told reporters in Gaza. ''We are ready to have
Jerusalem as an open city for all religions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Israel took over east Jerusalem from Jordanian occupation
in the 1967 Mideast war, all faiths have had access to their holy
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, meanwhile, is sensitive to other Arab leaders as the
negotiations proceed.
</P>
<P>
   After Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak traveled to Saudi Arabia
on Sunday for talks with King Fahd, Saudi officials said the two
leaders were anxious to ensure that at least part of Jerusalem
would come under Palestinian sovereignty. Mubarak also was expected
to talk in coming days with Syria's new President Bashar Assad and
Jordan's King Abdullah II, in their capitals or his.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State Department's Mideast summit home page:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/nea/cdavid--summit.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
