<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Raid Parliament  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Two hundred protesters threw bottles and
eggs and toppled automobiles then stormed into the Turkish
parliament on Cyrpus Monday, demanding government reimbursement for
money lost in the collapse of six banks.
</P>
<P>
   Police quickly pushed the demonstrators from the building,
arresting 10, Turkey's semi-official Anatolia news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament canceled its meeting after the protesters stormed in
and Prime Minister Dervis Eroglu met with representatives of the
demonstrators, Anatolia reported.
</P>
<P>
   The protest started when about 1,000 people gathered in a
Nicosia park to protest the government's failure to reimburse
depositors who lost their saving when six Turkish Cypriot banks
collapsed earlier this year amid allegations of bad management.
</P>
<P>
   The government had drawn up a plan to give depositors a total of
about $16 million, but the plan has not yet been implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations are rare in Turkish Cyprus, a small community
estimated at about 200,000 whose administration is recognized only
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been divided into a Turkish-occupied north and a
Greek-controlled south since Turkey invaded the island in 1974
after a short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
