<HEADLINE> Infected mosquitoes found in Central Park; spraying begins  </HEADLINE>
by 
n0916nyny-
u n BC-NY--WestNileVirus 1stLd-Writethru   07-24 0522
BC-NY--West Nile Virus, 1st Ld-Writethru,520   
Infected mosquitoes found in Central Park; spraying begins   
Eds: NEW throughout to UPDATE with spraying begun in Central Park;
ADDS Web address, photo tag
AP Photo NYR134
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Mosquitoes carrying the West Nile Virus have
been found in Central Park and on Staten Island, prompting city
officials to order the park closed Monday night and canceling a
concert that had been expected to draw 30,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The city began spraying the park with insecticide at 10 p.m.
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, on Wednesday, the ground spraying will expand
to Manhattan between 23rd and 110th streets. Spraying previously
scheduled for Staten Island on Monday night and parts of Queens and
Brooklyn on Tuesday also was to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said residents should not be alarmed by
the discovery of infected mosquitoes or the ground spraying of the
synthetic pesticides Sumithrin and Resmethrin, which could cause
breathing problems for the elderly and people with respiratory
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public should not have a great deal of apprehension,''
Giuliani told a City Hall press conference. ''Go about your lives
normally, but for one night, stay out of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   The park closed at 9:30 p.m., postponing a free performance by
the New York Philharmonic and a road race for children. Giuliani
said the concert likely would be held Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of infected mosquitoes marks the first time that
the potentially deadly West Nile virus has been found in mosquitoes
in the city this year. Earlier this summer, the virus was found in
birds and mosquitoes in the suburbs that ring the city.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the West Nile virus killed seven people and infected
62 others in the New York metropolitan area, prompting the city and
neighboring areas to undertake a massive campaign of aerial and
ground spraying.
</P>
<P>
   To staunch a new outbreak this year, the city embarked on a
program of trapping and testing mosquitoes, placing flocks of
sentinel chickens around the city to detect the presence of the
virus early and placing mosquito larvae-eating fish in water
treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious cases, the West Nile virus causes infection
resulting in encephalitis, or swelling of the brain. Elderly
individuals or those with weakened immune systems are most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The infected mosquitoes were found in Central Park near 63rd
Street on the east side of the park and in Staten Island in the
Fresh Kills landfill and Pond Park.
</P>
<P>
   Despite protests about the insecticides' potential risk to human
health and animal life, Giuliani said he was primarily concerned
with human life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to wait until it (the virus) shows up in human
beings like it did last year,'' Giuliani said. ''And I'm sorry, but
if it (the insecticide) kills animals, it kills animals. My job as
mayor of New York City is to help protect human life as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   -----:
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   New York State Health Department site:
http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
