<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Militant Group To Talk With India  </HEADLINE>
By QAISER MIRZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- A pro-Pakistan militant group in Kashmir
on Monday declared a cease-fire for three months, saying it was
ready to hold peace talks with the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Majid Dar, chief commander of the Hizbul Mujahideen group,
gave the Indian government one week to end what he called the
crackdown on Kashmiri militants.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is no positive response from the Indian government,
we will resume fighting the Indian forces,'' Dar told reporters in
Srinagar, the summer capital of India's Jammu-Kashmir state.
</P>
<P>
   In New Delhi, the Indian government welcomed the militant
outfit's decision. ''Any move which points toward peace is welcome.
The government, however, will be watching the situation closely and
make its assessment later,'' said Swagat Ghosh, the home ministry
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Dar's unilateral cease-fire announcement came as a surprise
since the Hizbul Mujahideen group has been in the forefront of
fighting the Indian security forces in Indian-controlled Kashmir
since the outbreak of insurgency in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen groups are fighting the secessionist war in
Kashmir, most seeking independence or union with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other insurgency group, the Ul-Umar Mujahideen,
indicated reservations about the initiative, saying it will not
allow any one to nullify the sacrifices made by the Kashmiri people
fighting for an independent Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, New Delhi has offered to hold talks with the
militants in Kashmir within the framework of the Indian
Constitution, implying that it would not accept any demand for
secession from India.
</P>
<P>
   Dar said the Indian government should lift its ban on the
assembly of more than five people in Kashmir and give people
freedom to express their views openly.
</P>
<P>
   India accuses Pakistan of training and army militants in
Kashmir, a charge Pakistan denies.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan have fought two wars over control of Kashmir
since they won independence from Britain in 1947. India governs
two-thirds of Kashmir and Pakistan the remaining one-third. Both
claim Kashmir in its entirety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
