<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush, Gore Race Remains Close  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The presidential race between George W. Bush
and Al Gore remains close in the days before the Republican
National Convention, says a new poll, though Bush holds persistent
underlying advantages on voters' perception of several key personal
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of voters saw Bush, the Republican governor of Texas,
as unlikely to keep the budget balanced while cutting income taxes;
more thought Vice President Gore had a better knowledge of world
affairs, according to an ABC News-Washington Post poll released
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bush is maintaining a lead on internal measures on many issues
and personal qualities and is in a strong position,'' said ABC
pollster Gary Langer. ''But now is when voters really start paying
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had 48 percent to 45 percent for Democrat Gore in the
ABC-Post poll, not a significant change from the 49-45 edge Bush
had in June. A four-way matchup also showed little change from
June, with Bush at 44 percent, Gore at 39 percent, Ralph Nader at 7
percent and Pat Buchanan at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another poll out Monday night, from CBS and The New York Times,
gave Bush 46 percent to 40 percent for Gore, compared with 43
percent for Bush and 41 percent for Gore earlier this month. Bush
also had a slim lead in that poll's 4-way matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Both polls, the CBS-Times survey of 953 adults and the ABC-Post
poll of 1,228 adults, were taken Friday through Sunday and had
error margins of 3 percentage points, slightly higher for
registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   On personal qualities, Bush held a double-digit lead in five
areas -- personality, leadership, trustworthiness, speaking his mind
and bringing change to Washington, according to the ABC-Post poll.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led on the issues of holding taxes down, handling the
national economy, handling the budget surplus and handling crime.
Gore led on health care, protecting the environment and addressing
women's issues. They were about even on education, Social Security
and handling the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS-Times poll found that health care was at the top of
campaign issues and Gore had an advantage on that issue as well as
protecting the environment and appointing justices to keep abortion
legal. Bush had the edge on reducing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in that poll saw Bush more favorably, 44 percent to 26
percent unfavorable, than Gore, 36 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both polls found Bush with an advantage on leadership qualities
and trust, while Gore had the advantage on caring about people like
them.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Langer noted that the nation's ambivalence over continuing
the direction set by the Clinton administration or changing could
help keep the race close.
</P>
<P>
   In both surveys, those polled were about evenly split on whether
the president should take the country in a new direction or keep it
moving along the path President Clinton has been taking it.
</P>
<P>
   Langer said one issue where Bush has a liability is the public
perception of his attitudes about the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Americans were twice as likely to think Bush was inclined to
favor the wealthy,'' he said. ''It was not as bad as it was for his
father (former President Bush), but it is a point of
vulnerability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
