<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-24 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schulters Arrives at 49ers Camp  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- Safety Lance Schulters showed up at the
San Francisco 49ers' training camp Monday after missing the first
six days and amassing $30,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Schulters, a Pro Bowl starter last season, blamed his absence on
''bad timing and miscommunication'' -- and a change of agents.
</P>
<P>
   He fired agent Alan Herman and hired Steve Weinberg last week.
There is a league-mandated transition time of several days in
switching agents, and the 49ers said they wouldn't negotiate with
anyone until Schulters came to camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really wasn't holding out,'' Schulters said. ''I was waiting
for them to talk to my agent. I couldn't officially hire him until
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulters is in the final year of a three-year contract that
will pay him the league minimum, $358,000, and he wanted Herman to
work on an extension. But Schulters is due to be a restricted free
agent after the season, which means the 49ers can match any other
team's offer and get compensation if he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't getting too much feedback from my other agent,''
Schulters said. ''I switched agents and was looking for a call back
from (49ers vice president) John McVay. I was waiting to talk to
him before I came in.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulters, a fourth-round pick out of Hofstra in 1998, replaced
Merton Hanks last season at free safety and tied for third in the
NFC with six interceptions. He will switch to strong safety this
year to replace Tim McDonald, who was waived and then retired.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lance is a big, strong, powerful guy and we're really glad to
have him back,'' general manager Bill Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have also agreed to a contract with first-round pick
Julian Peterson. Walsh said the Michigan State linebacker could be
in camp Wednesday.
</P>
